const TESTS = [
 {name:"Greenwood Community College", blurb:"Enrolment · Campus map · Pottery project · History of pottery",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Course enrolment (phone enquiry)", sp:["Officer","Caller"], instr:"Complete the enrolment table below. Write your answer in each gap using the word limit shown for that item.", layout:"table", table:[["Enquiry detail","Information given"],["Family name of applicant","{1}"],["Subject chosen","{2}"],["Ability group","{3}"],["Month the term opens","{4}"],["Weekday of the lesson","{5}"],["Time the session begins","{6}"],["Cost of the whole term (£)","{7}"],["Location (room)","{8}"],["Item to take along","an {9}"],["Chosen way of paying","{10}"]], intro:"a telephone conversation between an enrolment officer at a community college and a caller wanting to join an evening course", tr1:["Good morning, Greenwood Community College, admissions office speaking. How can I help you today?","Hello. I'd like to enrol on one of your evening courses, if there are still places available.","Certainly, we do still have a few spaces. Let me open a new form for you. First of all, could I take your surname, please?","Yes, of course. My surname is Hopkins. Let me spell that for you: H-O-P-K-I-N-S. Hopkins.","Thank you, I've got that. H-O-P-K-I-N-S, Hopkins. And which of our courses were you hoping to join?","I was looking at the Pottery course. I've always wanted to try working with clay, so the Pottery course would be perfect for me.","A lovely choice. We actually run two versions of it. Is that the beginner level you want, or were you after the more experienced group?","Definitely beginner. I've never made anything before, so I'd better start at the beginner level.","No problem at all. Now, let me check when that one gets going. The beginner group doesn't start straight away — it opens in September, once the new term is under way.","September's absolutely fine for me. And which day of the week does it run on?","Let me see. The beginner pottery classes are held once a week, on Thursday evenings. So that's every Thursday from September onwards.","Thursday suits me nicely, since I'm always free at the end of the week."], tr2:["Great. Now let me give you the timing. Classes begin at seven — oh, sorry, let me correct that, they actually start at half past six. So that's half past six in the evening, six thirty.","Half past six, got it. That gives me plenty of time to get there after work. And how much does the course cost?","The fee depends on the group. For the advanced class it's one hundred and fifty pounds for the term, but you're joining the beginner term, and that one is one hundred and twenty pounds.","So one hundred and twenty pounds for the beginner term. That seems very reasonable. Whereabouts do the classes actually take place?","They're held in room forty... no, sorry, let me read that again — room fourteen. Yes, it's room fourteen, on the ground floor.","Room fourteen, I'll remember that. Is there anything I need to bring along with me on the first evening?","It's a good idea to bring an apron if you have one, because working with the clay can get rather messy. So just an apron and something to write with.","An apron, right, I'll dig one out of a cupboard. And finally, how would you like me to pay?","You can pay by card, by cash, or by cheque, whichever is easiest for you.","I'll pay by card, please, if that's all right with you.","Card is perfect. That's everything booked in for you, Mr Hopkins. We look forward to seeing you in September."], Q:[{"q":"The caller gives the receptionist their family name.","a":"Hopkins","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The evening class the caller wishes to sign up for.","a":"pottery","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The experience group the caller decides to join.","a":"beginner","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The month in which the new term gets under way.","a":"September","lim":"A DATE"},{"q":"The single day each week on which the class meets.","a":"Thursday","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The corrected time at which each lesson opens.","a":"6.30|6:30|half past six","lim":"A TIME"},{"q":"The price the caller must pay for the term.","a":"120|one hundred and twenty","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The ground-floor room where lessons are held.","a":"14|fourteen","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The garment the caller is advised to bring along.","a":"apron","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The method the caller selects for settling the fee.","a":"card","lim":"ONE WORD"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Campus tour", map:PLAN, intro:"a college guide showing a group of new students around a plan of the campus", tr1:"Right everyone, welcome, and let me show you around the campus plan before we set off on the walking tour. If you look at the sheet in front of you, you'll see the main entrance marked at the bottom of the plan, right in the middle. That's where we are standing at the moment. Let's start at the top of the plan and work our way round. In the very top left-hand corner, on the far left of the top row, is our library, which stays open until nine most evenings. Now let your eye travel all the way across the top row to the opposite end. In the top right-hand corner, at the far right, you'll find the cafe, where you can get a hot drink between classes. Coming back down to the lower row now, the sports hall sits in the bottom left-hand corner, directly below the library. Next, look again along the top row, just to the right of the centre: that is where the pottery studio is, sitting between the middle of the top and the cafe. It's the room you'll be using for your course this term. And finally for this first group of places, think about the entrance again at the bottom middle. As you come in through that main entrance, reception is immediately on your right, just to the right of the doorway on the lower row, so it's the very first place you reach when you arrive.", tr2:"Now let's fill in the rest of the plan. Go back up to the top row once more. We've already placed the library on the far left and the cafe on the far right of that row. The music room is along the top as well, just to the left of the centre — so it sits between the library and the pottery studio, just left of the middle of the top row. Next, the car park. That takes up the whole of the bottom right-hand corner, on the far right of the lower row, so it is directly below the cafe and as far from the sports hall as you can possibly get. Then we have the exhibition space. Picture the entrance at the bottom middle again: the exhibition space is at the bottom just to the left of the entrance, on the lower row, so it sits between the sports hall and the doorway, directly opposite reception across the entrance. That completes the map. A couple of quick facts before we set off. People often think the college is older than it really is. Some visitors guess it opened in nineteen seventy-five, but in fact Greenwood was founded in nineteen eighty-five, so we're not quite as ancient as we might look. And one practical note: although we do have that car park, most of our students don't actually drive here. A few come in by train, but the great majority travel to college by bus, so the bus stop right outside the gates is very handy indeed.", Q:[{"q":"Where on the plan is the building that lends out books located?","a":"A"},{"q":"Which spot marks the place selling hot drinks and snacks?","a":"D"},{"q":"Where is the hall used for physical exercise positioned?","a":"E"},{"q":"Which location is the room set aside for clay work?","a":"C"},{"q":"Where do arriving visitors find the welcome desk?","a":"G"},{"q":"Which spot holds the room used for playing instruments?","a":"B"},{"q":"Where on the plan can vehicles be parked?","a":"H"},{"q":"Which location shows the area for displaying artwork?","a":"F"},{"q":"In which year did the college first open?","a":"B","o":["1975","1985","1995"]},{"q":"How do the majority of learners get to the college?","a":"C","o":["car","train","bus"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Two students plan a project", sp:["Student","Sam"], intro:"a conversation between two pottery students planning a project together", tr1:["Right, Sam, we really need to sort out our pottery project. What do you think it should actually be about?","Well, I did think about making a set of mugs at first, but honestly I think we should make a set of bowls instead. Bowls give us far more to work with.","Bowls sound great, let's do that — a set of bowls it is, then. Now, which clay shall we use for them?","I'd say let's use stoneware. It's really strong and it survives the kiln well, much better than the alternatives would for this.","Stoneware it is, then. Good thinking, we don't want them cracking on us. When is the whole thing actually due?","The tutor said we have to hand it in by the end of term. Not next week, and not this Friday like the sketchbook — the full project is due right at the end of term.","The end of term, okay, that gives us a bit of breathing space. And where shall we work on it?","I think working in the studio is best. The clay and the kiln are all there, so we won't have to carry anything around. Definitely the studio rather than a classroom.","Agreed, the studio makes complete sense. So what do you reckon is going to be the hardest part of all this?","Honestly, I'd say the glazing. Shaping the bowls is fine, and drying them is easy enough, but getting an even colour with the glaze is really tricky."], tr2:["That's true, the glazing will definitely need care. So how many pieces do we actually need to make in total?","We need six altogether. Not four, and not eight — the brief clearly asks for a set of six bowls.","Six bowls, got it. Now, someone has to write up the report. How shall we split the work between us?","Tell you what, I'll write the report if you take the photos of each stage. I quite enjoy the writing side of things.","That works for me. So just to be clear, you, Sam, are doing the report, and I'll handle all the photos. And what about the presentation — how long does it have to be?","The presentation has to be ten minutes long. Not five, and not eight — she was very clear that it's a full ten minutes for each group.","Ten minutes, fine. One more thing I wasn't sure about — should we use the wheel for these bowls?","No, let's not use the wheel. The tutor prefers hand-building, so we'll shape them by hand rather than throwing them on the wheel. We'll still use the kiln and the glaze, obviously, just not the wheel.","Fair enough, no wheel then. Did she give us any other advice before we start?","She did, actually. She suggested more practice with the clay before we begin — not buying new tools or reading a book, just getting our hands used to the clay first."], Q:[{"q":"What items have the pair agreed to produce for their project?","a":"B","o":["mugs","bowls","tiles"]},{"q":"Which type of clay do the students settle on?","a":"A","o":["stoneware","porcelain","earthenware"]},{"q":"When does the finished work have to be submitted?","a":"C","o":["next week","Friday","the close of term"]},{"q":"Which location will they carry out the work in?","a":"B","o":["the library","the studio","the classroom"]},{"q":"Which stage do they expect to find the most difficult?","a":"C","o":["forming the shape","letting them dry","applying the glaze"]},{"q":"How many finished items must the pair make altogether?","a":"B","o":["four","six","eight"]},{"q":"Who has agreed to produce the written write-up?","a":"A","o":["Sam","the other student","the two of them"]},{"q":"What length must the spoken presentation be?","a":"C","o":["five minutes","eight minutes","ten minutes"]},{"q":"Which piece of equipment do they choose to avoid?","a":"B","o":["the kiln","the wheel","the glaze"]},{"q":"What did the tutor recommend they do beforehand?","a":"A","o":["get more used to the clay","purchase new tools","read a book"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: history of pottery", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below. Fill each gap with a word or number, keeping within the limit shown for that step.", layout:"flow", flow:["Earliest pots appear more than {1} thousand years ago","Firing soft clay in a fire makes it both hard and {2}","First pots are shaped by hand from stacked coils of {3}","Later the potter's {4} lets round vessels be formed rapidly","Pots are hardened at high heat inside an oven known as a {5}","A glassy coating called {6} is added to seal and colour the surface","In China a fine, thin, pure white ware named {7} is perfected","Its high value earns it the nickname white {8}","The wheel is dated back to roughly {9} BC","Today many still shape pots by hand simply as an enjoyable {10}"], intro:"a lecturer giving a talk to students about the history of pottery", tr1:"Good afternoon everyone. Today we're going to look at the history of pottery, which is one of humanity's oldest and most fascinating crafts. When you make a pot in the studio this term, you are taking part in a tradition that stretches back an extraordinarily long way. In fact, the earliest known pots were made more than ten thousand years ago. That's right, over ten thousand years — long before writing existed, and long before the wheel was used for carts. What our distant ancestors discovered was really quite remarkable. They found that if you shape soft clay and then heat it in a fire, something changes: the clay becomes hard, and, crucially, it also becomes waterproof. That combination of being both hard and waterproof is exactly what you need if you want to store grain or carry water, so pottery quickly became essential to everyday life. Now, how were these very first pots actually made? They were built entirely by hand, without any machinery at all. A common method was to roll the clay into long, thin coils — coils of clay, stacked up in rings, one on top of another, and then smoothed together to form the walls of the pot. A major advance came later with the invention of the potter's wheel, which allowed round vessels to be shaped quickly and very evenly. And to make the pots really tough, people fired them at very high temperatures in a special kind of oven that we call a kiln.", tr2:"So we've reached the point where pots are being fired in the kiln. The next great step forward was decoration and sealing. Potters learned to coat their work with glaze. Glaze is a thin, glassy layer that melts in the heat of the kiln and seals the surface of the pot, making it watertight and, at the same time, adding beautiful colour. So do remember that word: glaze, the glassy coating that seals the surface. Moving on to a particular high point in the story, we travel across to China. There, over many centuries, craftsmen perfected a very fine, very thin, pure white pottery known as porcelain. Porcelain was so delicate and so highly prized in Europe that people there gave it a special nickname: they called it white gold. Just imagine that — pottery so valuable that it was compared to gold itself, white gold. Now let me come back to a date I promised you, about the potter's wheel. That invention wasn't recent at all; the wheel first appeared around three thousand five hundred BC, that is roughly three and a half thousand years before the common era. Finally, let's think about the present day. Although modern factories now produce pottery by the million on their production lines, a great many people still love making pots by hand. For them it isn't work at all — it is simply a relaxing and rewarding hobby.", Q:[{"q":"How many thousands of years back do the first known pots reach?","a":"ten|10","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Besides becoming hard, what other useful quality does fired clay gain?","a":"waterproof","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The earliest pots were formed from rolled coils of this material.","a":"clay","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The device whose arrival allowed even, speedy shaping of pots.","a":"wheel","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The name of the special oven used for firing the pots.","a":"kiln","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The glassy melting layer that waterproofs and colours a pot.","a":"glaze","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The delicate white ceramic developed by Chinese craftsmen.","a":"porcelain","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Europeans likened this prized ware to which precious metal?","a":"gold","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The approximate year, before the common era, when the wheel emerged.","a":"3500","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"For many people, hand-making pots today is a relaxing what?","a":"hobby","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"Riverside Leisure Centre", blurb:"Membership · Park site plan · Weekend plan · Urban parks lecture",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Membership registration", sp:["Officer","Caller"], instr:"Complete the table below. Write the answer for each numbered gap using the word limit shown beside it.", layout:"table", table:[["Detail","Information given"],["Family name of the applicant","{1}"],["Category of membership selected","{2}"],["Amount charged every month","£{3}"],["Month the membership will commence","{4}"],["Activity the applicant prefers most","{5}"],["Refundable charge for a locker","£{6}"],["Weekday on which the family session runs","{7}"],["Family name of the coach (Mr ...)","{8}"],["Item to bring on the first visit: photo ...","{9}"],["Way the applicant wishes to be reached","{10}"]], intro:"a phone conversation between a leisure centre officer and a caller who wants to join", tr1:["Good morning and welcome to Riverside Leisure Centre. How can I help you today?","Hello there. I've walked past this place so many times, and I've finally decided that I'd like to join as a member.","That's wonderful to hear. I can set everything up for you now. Let me start with a few details. Could I take your surname, please?","Yes, of course. It's Franklin. Let me spell that out so there's no mistake, F-R-A-N-K-L-I-N, Franklin.","Franklin, lovely, I've got that down. And which type of membership were you thinking of? We offer an individual membership and a family membership.","Well, there are four of us at home, so I think the family option makes the most sense. Yes, let's go with the family membership, please.","An excellent choice. Just so you're aware of the pricing, the individual membership costs thirty pounds a month, whereas the family membership works out at forty-five pounds a month, and that covers everybody in your household.","Forty-five pounds a month sounds very reasonable for all four of us, so that's absolutely fine by me.","Great, I'll put you down for that. And when would you like your membership to begin?","Could it start from the first of May? That gives me a couple of weeks to get organised. Yes, from the first of May, please.","The first of May it is. Now, out of all the things we offer here, which activity interests you the most?","Oh, without a doubt, swimming. I try to get in the pool whenever I can, so swimming is definitely my main interest."], tr2:["That's noted, swimming as your main activity. Now let me run through a few practical things. If you'd like to use one of our lockers, please be aware they require a small deposit. It's just, sorry, let me get this right, not one pound, it's a two-pound deposit, and it's fully refundable when you return the key.","A two-pound deposit, that's no problem at all. I'll remember to bring a spare coin.","Perfect. Since you've chosen the family membership, you might also enjoy our family class. It runs once a week, and at the moment it's held on Mondays. So if Monday suits you, the whole family is welcome to come along.","Monday works really well for us, actually, as none of us are busy on that day. And who runs the class?","It's led by one of our most experienced instructors. His name is Mr Wright, and I'll spell that because people often get it wrong, W-R-I-G-H-T, Wright. He's absolutely brilliant with families and children.","Mr Wright, got it, thank you. Is there anything in particular I need to bring when I first come in?","Yes, just one thing to remember for your first visit. Please bring some photo ID along with you, a driving licence or a passport is perfect. We only need to check the photo ID once, to confirm your details.","Photo ID, understood. I'll pop my passport in my bag so that I don't forget it.","Lovely. And finally, how would you prefer us to contact you about class timetables and any changes?","By email, please. Email is by far the easiest way to reach me, and I check my inbox every single day."], Q:[{"q":"State the applicant's family name.","a":"Franklin","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Name the type of membership that was chosen.","a":"family","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Give the fee paid each month.","a":"45|forty-five","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Say which month the membership starts.","a":"May|1st May|first of May","lim":"A DATE"},{"q":"Give the pastime the applicant enjoys the most.","a":"swimming","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"State the returnable sum paid for a locker.","a":"2|two","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Name the day of the week set aside for the family session.","a":"Monday","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Give the surname of the person who leads the session.","a":"Wright","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Name the kind of photo document required at the first visit.","a":"ID|identification","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"State how the applicant would rather be contacted.","a":"email","lim":"ONE WORD"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Riverside Park", map:PARK, intro:"a park guide describing the layout of Riverside Park to a group of visitors", tr1:"Right everyone, if you could all gather round, I'd like to give you a quick tour of the plan of Riverside Park before we set off, so that you know exactly where everything is. Let's begin down at the bottom of the map, in the very middle, because that's where the main entrance is, the very point where we're all standing right now. As you come through that entrance and look around, the first thing you'll probably want to find is the cafe, and that sits just to the right of the entrance, so do keep it in mind for later when you fancy a cup of tea. Directly opposite, just to the left of the entrance, are the toilets, so they're an easy pair to remember, cafe on the one side and toilets on the other. Now let your eye travel right up to the top of the map. Up in the top left-hand corner you'll spot the children's playground, which is always very popular with families. Then, if you look right across to the opposite side, the top right-hand corner is where you'll find the boat hire, down by the water's edge, where you can rent yourself a little rowing boat. Finally for now, come back down to the bottom of the map and look over to the far left. Tucked away in the bottom left-hand corner is the bird hide, a lovely quiet little spot for anyone who enjoys watching the wildlife among the reeds.", tr2:"Now let's fill in all the spaces in between, and we'll start once more along the top of the map. We've already spotted the children's playground sitting in the top left-hand corner. Moving across to the right of that, just to the left of centre along the top, you'll come to the picnic area, a lovely grassy space with benches and tables where you're very welcome to sit down and eat your lunch. Carry on in the very same direction, and just to the right of centre along the top, you'll reach the information point, where a member of staff can answer any of your questions and hand out leaflets and maps. Then, as I said a moment ago, the boat hire is right beside it in the top right-hand corner. That just leaves the bottom right-hand corner of the map, and that whole area is taken up by the car park, so that's where you should head if you happen to have driven here today. A couple of final reminders before we go in. The park opens nice and early, at eight o'clock in the morning, so there's plenty of time for a proper full day out. And one really important rule, we're all very fond of our wildlife here, so dogs must be kept on a lead at all times, please, and never allowed to run free. Right then, let's head off and enjoy the park.", Q:[{"q":"Where on the plan is the area where youngsters can play?","a":"A"},{"q":"Where can visitors rent a rowing boat by the water?","a":"D"},{"q":"Whereabouts is the spot serving hot drinks and snacks?","a":"G"},{"q":"Where are the washrooms located?","a":"F"},{"q":"Where is the sheltered place for quietly observing wildlife?","a":"E"},{"q":"Where is the grassy area with tables for eating lunch?","a":"B"},{"q":"Where would you go to ask staff a question or collect a leaflet?","a":"C"},{"q":"Where should drivers leave their vehicles?","a":"H"},{"q":"At what time does the park first open in the morning?","a":"B","o":["seven o'clock","eight o'clock","nine o'clock"]},{"q":"What is the rule about dogs inside the park?","a":"C","o":["they must stay at home","they may roam freely","they have to be kept on a lead"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Two friends plan a weekend", sp:["Friend A","Friend B"], intro:"two friends discussing their plans for a day out at the weekend", tr1:["So, I was thinking, shall we finally have that day out at Riverside Park this weekend? We keep saying we will and then never do.","Yes, let's genuinely do it this time. For me, Saturday would be much better than Sunday, because I've promised to visit my gran on the Sunday. So shall we make it the Saturday?","Saturday's perfect, I've got nothing on that day. Now, how are we going to get there? It's a fair old distance.","Well, we could catch the bus, but honestly I'd much rather cycle. It's really not far at all by bicycle, and it's a lovely ride along the river. Let's just take our bikes.","Good idea, cycling it is. What about food? Should we take something with us, or buy it once we're there?","Oh, we should definitely bring our own lunch. I've eaten at the cafe in the park before and, to be blunt, it's terribly expensive for what you get. So packing our own sandwiches will save us a fortune.","Fair enough, homemade lunch it is. And once we're there, what's the one thing you most want to do?","You know what I'd absolutely love? Going boating out on the lake. There's nothing better than being on the water on a sunny day. Boating is top of my list.","Me too, I'm completely up for a spot of boating. Is there anything you're worried might spoil the day?","The only thing on my mind is the weather, to be honest. I checked the forecast this morning and there's rain predicted, so let's hope it holds off. It's the weather that concerns me, nothing else."], tr2:["Right, so where shall we actually meet up on the Saturday morning? Somewhere nice and easy to find.","Let's just meet at the main entrance, I reckon that's easiest for both of us. Everyone knows where the entrance is, so we can't go wrong. Not the cafe and not the car park, just the entrance.","The entrance, agreed. And what time should we aim for? I don't want to be standing around waiting for ages.","Shall we say half past nine? I think nine thirty is a good time, early enough for a full day but not a painfully early start. So let's meet at nine thirty.","Half past nine suits me nicely. After we've done the boating, is there anything else you fancy seeing?","Yes, once we're off the water, I'd really like to go and see the birds from the hide. Apparently you can spot all sorts of interesting species there. Watching the birds would be a lovely way to spend an hour.","That sounds great. Is there anywhere you'd rather steer clear of?","Definitely the playground, let's avoid that one. It gets absolutely packed with families on Saturdays and it's far too noisy and crowded for me. So we'll give the playground a miss.","Agreed, we'll skip the playground. And just in case that rain really does arrive, do we have a backup plan?","Good thinking. If it truly pours down, our plan B is to head into town and visit the museum instead. It's indoors, it's interesting, and it'll keep us dry. So the museum is our rainy-day option."], Q:[{"q":"Which day have the friends settled on for their outing?","a":"B","o":["on Sunday","on Saturday","on Friday"]},{"q":"How have they decided to reach the park?","a":"C","o":["by public bus","by car","on their bikes"]},{"q":"Why are they packing their own meal?","a":"A","o":["the park cafe charges too much","the park has no cafe","home food is more nutritious"]},{"q":"What do they most want to do at the park?","a":"B","o":["angling","going out on a boat","riding bikes"]},{"q":"What is the one thing they feel anxious about?","a":"C","o":["how much it will cost","how busy it will be","what the weather will do"]},{"q":"Which spot have they picked as their meeting point?","a":"A","o":["by the main gate","at the cafe","in the car park"]},{"q":"At what time do they plan to gather?","a":"B","o":["nine o'clock","half past nine","ten o'clock"]},{"q":"What else would they like to look at while there?","a":"C","o":["the fish","the flowers","the birdlife"]},{"q":"Which part of the park do they intend to keep away from?","a":"A","o":["the play area","the lake","the cafe"]},{"q":"What will they do instead if it rains heavily?","a":"B","o":["return home","go round the museum","sit in the cafe"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: urban parks and wellbeing", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below. Write the answer for each numbered gap using the word limit shown beside it.", layout:"flow", flow:["Spending time in parks lifts our mental {1}","This is chiefly because closeness to {2} eases stress","Parks also prompt people to do more physical {3}","The earliest park built for the public was {4} Park","It first opened its gates in the year {5}","In hot weather, trees bring down the {6} of built-up areas","By supplying food and shelter, parks help protect {7}","The biggest difficulty today is a shortage of {8}","A workable remedy is to depend on the help of {9}","In years to come, parks may add shared community {10}"], intro:"a lecturer talking to students about urban parks and their effect on wellbeing", tr1:"Good morning everyone, and thank you for coming to today's lecture on urban parks and the many ways in which they contribute to our wellbeing. Let's begin with the benefits, and there are quite a number of them. The first and perhaps most striking benefit is the effect that parks have on our minds. A growing body of research now shows that spending time in green spaces can genuinely improve our mental health. People who live close to a park and use it regularly report lower levels of anxiety and a far greater sense of calm. So why should that be? Well, the evidence points to one simple factor above all others, and that is contact with nature. It turns out that even a short walk among trees and grass helps to reduce stress, lowering the levels of stress hormones in the body. So contact with nature really is at the heart of it. But the benefits are not only mental, they are physical too. Parks actively encourage people to take more physical exercise. Just think about it, in any park you'll see people walking their dogs, jogging along the paths, cycling, or playing games on the open grass. That kind of everyday physical exercise soon adds up and keeps us all healthier. Now, let me give you a little history. The very first public park designed specifically for ordinary citizens, rather than for royalty or the wealthy, was Birkenhead Park. This remarkable green space opened its gates in the year eighteen forty-seven, and it set the pattern for public parks right around the world.", tr2:"Let's move on now from history to the environment, because parks do a great deal of good for our cities in that respect too. Consider for a moment what happens during a hot summer. Cities built of concrete and tarmac can become terribly warm, but the trees in our parks help enormously here. Through the shade they cast and the moisture they release, those trees lower the temperature of the surrounding streets, sometimes by several degrees, making the whole city far more bearable in a heatwave. On top of that, green spaces are absolutely vital for wildlife. By offering both food and shelter, parks support biodiversity, providing homes for the birds, insects and small mammals that would otherwise have nowhere to live in such a built-up area. Now, it isn't all good news, and we must be honest about the challenges. The main problem facing a great many parks today is really a financial one, a serious lack of funding from local councils, whose budgets have been squeezed tighter year after year. So what can actually be done? One practical solution that has worked well in many towns is to rely on volunteers, ordinary local residents who give up their weekends to plant, to weed and to tidy the grounds. Their tireless efforts keep a great many parks alive. And looking ahead to the future, planners have one particularly exciting idea. They hope that the parks of tomorrow will include community gardens, shared plots where residents can come together and grow their own fruit and vegetables. Thank you all very much.", Q:[{"q":"Name what parks improve in the mind.","a":"health","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"State what people need contact with to feel less stressed.","a":"nature","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Name the kind of physical activity parks encourage.","a":"exercise","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Give the name of the first park made for ordinary people.","a":"Birkenhead","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"State the year that park was opened.","a":"1847","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Say what trees reduce across a city in summer.","a":"temperature","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Name what parks safeguard by giving food and shelter.","a":"biodiversity|wildlife","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"State what parks mainly lack nowadays.","a":"funding","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Name the people whose unpaid work keeps parks going.","a":"volunteers","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"State what future parks may contain for growing produce.","a":"gardens","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"City Museum", blurb:"Tour booking · Museum quarter street map · Essay tutorial · History of museums",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Guided tour booking", sp:["Officer","Caller"], instr:"Complete the table below. Write ONE WORD AND/OR A NUMBER for each answer, keeping within the stated limit for each gap.", layout:"table", table:[["Booking detail","Information given"],["Family name of the person booking","{1}"],["Theme chosen for the tour","{2}"],["Total people expected in the party","{3}"],["Day in June that was booked","{4}"],["Time the tour is due to start","{5}"],["Amount charged for each group member","£{6}"],["Spot where everyone is to assemble","main {7}"],["Piece of equipment handed to each guest","{8}"],["Activity that is forbidden in the galleries","{9} photography"],["Total running time of the tour","{10} minutes"]], intro:"a telephone conversation between a museum bookings officer and a caller arranging a guided tour", tr1:["Good morning, you've reached the City Museum bookings line, this is the visitor services desk. How can I help you today?","Oh, hello. I'd like to book a guided tour for a group of us, please, if there's still space this month.","Of course, I'd be happy to arrange that. Could I take your name first, so I can start the booking?","Yes, certainly. My surname is Marshall, and let me spell that for you, that's M-A-R-S-H-A-L-L, Marshall.","Thank you, Mr Marshall, I've got that written down. Now, we run two tours here, an art tour and a history tour. Which would you prefer?","We were a bit tempted by the art one, but really it's the past of the city we're keen on, so we'll go for the history tour instead.","A lovely choice, the history tour is very popular. And roughly how many people will be coming along in your group?","There are eight of us altogether. Well, one friend might drop out, but let's say eight for now to be safe.","Eight it is, I'll make a note of that. And which date were you hoping to visit? We do get booked up quite quickly.","We were thinking of the thirteenth of June at first, but that turned out to be a work day, so let's make it the fourteenth of June if that's free.","Let me just check the fourteenth for you. Yes, that day is available. Would you like a morning slot or an afternoon one?","The morning would suit us best. I know the ten o'clock is often busy, so is the eleven o'clock tour still open for us to join?"], tr2:["Yes, the eleven o'clock morning tour still has room, so I'll pop your group into that slot. Now let me explain the cost to you.","Great, thank you. How much will it be, and is there any sort of reduction for a group like ours?","There is indeed. For an individual visitor the ticket is eight pounds each, but because you're a group the price comes down to six pounds per person.","Six pounds each, that really is very reasonable. And whereabouts should we all meet when we arrive on the day?","You'll want to gather at the main entrance of the museum, just by the front steps, and your guide will come out and collect you there.","The main entrance, understood. Is there anything provided to help us hear the guide clearly, since we're quite a large group?","Yes, that's a good question. Each visitor is given a headset when the tour begins, so you can hear every word even at the back of the group.","A headset each, that's really helpful. And are there any rules we should be aware of once we're inside the galleries?","Just one important thing to remember. Ordinary pictures are fine, but flash photography is not allowed inside, as the bright light can damage the older exhibits.","No flash photography, I'll make sure everyone knows that. And finally, how long does the whole tour actually last?","The history tour runs for about ninety minutes from start to finish, so you'll be finished well before lunchtime.","Ninety minutes, that's perfect. Thank you so much for all your help, we're really looking forward to it."], Q:[{"q":"Surname of the customer making the reservation","a":"Marshall","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Which of the two tours the group settled on","a":"history","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"How many visitors will be in the party","a":"8|eight","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The June date finally agreed for the visit","a":"14th|fourteenth|14","lim":"A DATE"},{"q":"The hour at which the chosen tour departs","a":"11|11am|eleven","lim":"A TIME"},{"q":"The reduced fare paid by each individual in the group","a":"6|six","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The part of the building where the group meets the guide","a":"entrance","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The listening device provided to every guest","a":"headset","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The kind of photography banned among the exhibits","a":"flash","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"How long the whole experience takes","a":"90|ninety","lim":"A NUMBER"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Museum quarter", map:STREET, intro:"a guide describing a street map of the museum quarter to a group of visitors", tr1:"Let me help you get your bearings on the street map of the museum quarter before we set off. First, find the main entrance to the whole area, which is marked at the very bottom of the map, right in the centre. From there, a corridor or walkway runs straight up the middle, separating the buildings along the top from those along the bottom. Let's start with the top row of buildings first. Right up in the top left-hand corner, as far left as you can go, stands the museum itself, our grand old building. Now move your eye a little to the right, still along the top but just to the left of the centre line, and that's where the art gallery sits, immediately next to the museum. Carry on rightwards across the top, and just to the right of centre you'll come to the town hall, with its tall clock tower. Keep going all the way to the end of the top row, and in the top right-hand corner you'll find the library, a modern glass building. Now let's drop down to the bottom row. Over on the far left, in the bottom left-hand corner beneath the museum, is the post office, where you can buy stamps and postcards. Do remember that one, because we shall pass it again later on the walk.", tr2:"Now for the rest of the bottom row and a few practical points. In the bottom right-hand corner, diagonally opposite the post office, you'll see the bank, which has a cash machine outside if you should need one. Coming back towards the middle of the bottom row, look on either side of that central entrance we found earlier. Just to the left of the entrance is the theatre, which puts on plays in the evening, and directly across from it, just to the right of the entrance, is the bus stop where the number twelve service calls. So the theatre and the bus stop face each other across the entrance. Now, a couple of useful details for your journey. Some of you asked about the train. The nearest railway station isn't far at all. You might think it's a good ten minutes on foot, but in fact it is only five minutes away walking, so it really is very handy. And for those of you who came by car, you may have expected on-street parking, but actually there isn't any along these roads. Instead, parking is available underground, in a car park beneath the square, so do keep your ticket for that.", Q:[{"q":"Whereabouts on the plan does the museum stand?","a":"A"},{"q":"In which position can the library be found?","a":"D"},{"q":"Pinpoint the location of the town hall.","a":"C"},{"q":"Where exactly is the art gallery placed?","a":"B"},{"q":"Identify the spot occupied by the post office.","a":"E"},{"q":"Where is the bank located on the map?","a":"H"},{"q":"Which point marks the theatre?","a":"F"},{"q":"At which position is the bus stop shown?","a":"G"},{"q":"How much walking time does it take to reach the closest railway station?","a":"B","o":["about two minutes on foot","roughly five minutes on foot","around ten minutes on foot"]},{"q":"What sort of parking is on offer for those who drove?","a":"C","o":["provided free of charge","alongside the kerb","in a lot below ground"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Tutor and student discuss an essay", sp:["Tutor","Student"], intro:"a tutor giving a student feedback on an essay about local history", tr1:["Come in, take a seat. I've had a good look through the draft essay you handed in. First of all, the subject you chose, the local history of the town, is a really solid topic, so no worries there.","Oh, that's a relief. I did wonder whether I should have written about science or art instead, but local history was the one that interested me most.","No, you made exactly the right call, so do stick with local history. Now, let's talk about length. Do you remember what word count I set for this assignment?","I think it was somewhere around a thousand words, wasn't it? Or was it fifteen hundred? I've honestly lost track.","It's actually two thousand words, and at the moment you're a little under that, so you'll need to build it out a bit. That part is easily fixed.","Right, two thousand, I'll add more. And was the way I organised everything alright, do you think?","That's actually the main problem, I'm afraid. It isn't your grammar, which is fine, and it isn't really the length either. It's the structure. The paragraphs jump around and don't follow a clear order.","I see, so it's the structure I really need to fix. I'll go back and reorganise the whole thing.","Please do. And one more thing on content. Your points need backing up. You have plenty of ideas and examples, but what's missing is evidence to support the claims you make.","More evidence, understood. And how would you like me to handle the references?","Good question. I don't want footnotes on this one, and please don't use the MLA system either. I'd like you to use the Harvard referencing style throughout.","Harvard style, got it. I'll make sure every source is cited properly."], tr2:["Now, I know you asked about timing. Given that you've been unwell recently, I don't want to rush you, so rather than keeping the original Wednesday deadline, I'll extend it. Let's say Friday. Would that give you enough time?","Friday would be perfect, thank you so much. Is there any reading you'd recommend to help me improve it?","Yes, definitely. Have a look at the textbook. Not chapter five, and you can skip the appendix for now, but chapter three in particular is very relevant to your argument.","Chapter three, I'll read it carefully. And was there anything about the opening that I should change?","There is, actually. Your introduction is the one part that lets it down. It's far too long. It isn't unclear or too short, quite the opposite. You just need to cut it right down.","I'll trim the introduction right back, then. And was there anything you thought actually worked well?","Absolutely. I have to say, the research behind this is excellent, really thorough. Your writing is decent and your referencing will be fine once corrected, but it's the research that genuinely impressed me.","That means a lot, thank you. Should we arrange another meeting to check my progress?","Yes, let's do that. Come back and see me on Monday, not Friday, and certainly well before the end of term, so we can go through your revised draft together.","Monday it is. Thanks again for all your feedback, I really do appreciate it."], Q:[{"q":"Which subject did the student decide to write about?","a":"B","o":["the sciences","the town and its local past","the arts"]},{"q":"What overall length was the assignment supposed to be?","a":"C","o":["one thousand words","fifteen hundred words","two thousand words"]},{"q":"What does the tutor see as the essay's chief weakness?","a":"A","o":["the way it is organised","the grammar used","the number of words"]},{"q":"What is the essay most short of?","a":"B","o":["fresh ideas","supporting proof","worked examples"]},{"q":"Which system of citation must the student adopt?","a":"C","o":["the MLA approach","notes at the foot of the page","the Harvard approach"]},{"q":"To which day has the hand-in date been pushed back?","a":"B","o":["Wednesday","Friday","Monday"]},{"q":"Which piece of reading does the tutor advise?","a":"A","o":["the third chapter","the fifth chapter","the appendix section"]},{"q":"What is the trouble with the opening of the essay?","a":"C","o":["it is far too brief","it comes across as unclear","it goes on for too long"]},{"q":"Which feature of the work does the tutor praise?","a":"B","o":["the writing itself","the investigation carried out","the citation of sources"]},{"q":"When are the two of them due to meet next?","a":"A","o":["on Monday","on Friday","once term has finished"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: history of museums", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below. Write ONE WORD AND/OR A NUMBER for each answer, staying within the limit shown for each gap.", layout:"flow", flow:["The label museum can be traced back to the {1} language, meaning a place devoted to learning","In ancient times the earliest gatherings of prized objects were kept in {2}, cared for by priests","The first modern public museum stood in the city of {3}, where it remains today","This institution first opened to visitors in the year {4}","Unlike private collections, it made its objects available to the {5}","During the 1800s imposing museums were put up chiefly to provide {6} for working people","In the present era visitors interact with the exhibits through touch-operated {7}","One difficulty that never goes away for any museum is limited {8}","As a consequence, the majority of items stay in {9} out of public view","Looking ahead, institutions intend to run {10} tours that people can enjoy from home"], intro:"part of a university lecture about the history of museums", tr1:"Good afternoon everyone. Today I want to trace the long history of the museum, from the ancient world right up to the present day. Let's begin with the word itself. The term museum comes originally from the Greek word mouseion, which meant a place dedicated to the muses, the goddesses who inspired learning and the arts. So from the very start, the idea carried a strong sense of scholarship. Now, where were the earliest collections of valuable objects kept? You might imagine grand palaces or private homes, but in fact the first great collections in the ancient world belonged to temples, where treasures and offerings were gathered together and looked after by the priests. Moving forward many centuries, we reach what is generally regarded as the first modern public museum. This was the Ashmolean, and it was not established in London, as many people assume, but in Oxford, where it still stands to this day. As for the date, it first opened its doors in sixteen eighty-three. What made it so significant was this. Unlike the earlier private collections, which only a wealthy few could ever see, the Ashmolean displayed its objects to the public, so that ordinary visitors could come inside and look.", tr2:"Let's now jump ahead to the nineteenth century, a great age of museum building. During that period, many grand and imposing museums were constructed across Europe, and their main purpose was not entertainment but education. The aim was quite explicitly to improve and instruct ordinary working people. If we turn to the present day, the picture changes again. Today, museums increasingly rely on technology to draw visitors in and hold their attention. You'll often find, for instance, interactive screens that let you explore an exhibit with the touch of a finger. There is, however, one constant challenge that every single museum faces, and that is space. It's a simple problem of size. Most museums can only put a small fraction of what they own on display at any one time. Because of this, the great majority of their objects are not on show at all, but are instead kept in storage, tucked away in rooms behind the scenes. And what about the future? Well, looking ahead, many institutions are now planning to offer virtual tours, using digital technology to allow people to explore the collections from the comfort of their own homes. Thank you, and I'll take any questions now.", Q:[{"q":"The origin of the term museum lies in this language","a":"Greek","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The type of building that housed the first great collections","a":"temples","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The town in which the first modern public museum was set up","a":"Oxford","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The year in which that museum admitted its first visitors","a":"1683","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The group to whom its exhibits were first shown","a":"public","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The purpose behind nineteenth-century museum building","a":"education","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The interactive devices found in museums nowadays","a":"screens","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The recurring problem of size that every museum meets","a":"space","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Where the bulk of a museum's holdings are kept","a":"storage","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The kind of tours museums plan to offer in future","a":"virtual","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"TechStart Company", blurb:"Job enquiry · Office plan · New project · Psychology of teamwork",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Job enquiry", sp:["HR","Caller"], instr:"Complete the table below. Write the answer for each gap and keep strictly to the word or number limit shown.", layout:"table", table:[["Detail","Applicant notes"],["Family name of caller","{1}"],["Post applied for","graphic {2}"],["Time worked in the field","{3} years"],["Earliest month she can begin","{4}"],["Pay she is asking for","around £{5}"],["Notice owed to current employer","{6} month"],["Where her sample work is displayed","{7}"],["Person supplying her reference (her current)","{8}"],["Day interviews are always held","{9}"],["Last three digits of her phone number","{10}"]], intro:"a telephone conversation between a company's HR officer and a person enquiring about a job", tr1:["TechStart HR, good afternoon, how can I help you today?","Hello, I'm calling about the job advert I saw online, and I'd like to ask a few questions before I apply.","Of course, I'd be glad to help. Could I take a few details first? May I have your surname, please?","Yes, it's Coleman, that's C-O-L-E-M-A-N, Coleman.","Thank you, Miss Coleman. And which position are you interested in? We're advertising several roles at the moment.","I'm interested in the graphic designer role, the creative one. I did wonder about the web developer post as well, but no, it's definitely the graphic designer position I want.","Lovely, the graphic designer vacancy it is. How much relevant experience do you have in that field?","I've been working professionally for three years now, all of it in design, so three years of solid experience.","That's good to hear. And when would you be able to start with us if you were successful?","Well, I first thought I could begin in July, but having checked my commitments, I'd actually need until August, so from August I'd be completely free.","Understood, August then. And may I ask what your salary expectation is for this role?","I was originally hoping for thirty-five thousand, but I've thought it over, and around thirty thousand pounds would be perfectly fine for me."], tr2:["Thirty thousand, noted. Now, if we did offer you the position, what notice period would you have to give your present employer?","My notice period is fairly short, just one month, so I could hand in my notice and be with you within one month.","One month is very manageable. Do you happen to have a portfolio that we could look at?","Yes, I do, and I keep it fully up to date. All of my recent work, including logos, brochures and packaging designs, is displayed on my website, so you can browse the full portfolio there whenever it suits you.","Perfect, we'll take a look at your website before we decide. Would you also be able to provide a professional reference to support your application?","Certainly. My current manager has already kindly agreed to write one for me, so the reference would come directly from my manager rather than from a colleague.","That's ideal, thank you. Just so you know, we hold all of our first-round interviews on Tuesdays, so if you're shortlisted we'd invite you in on a Tuesday, probably in the morning.","A Tuesday works very well for me, and mornings are perfect, thank you.","And finally, could I take a contact number so that our team can reach you if we need to?","Of course. I'll confirm the full number on my written application form, but it ends in seven-four-two, that's the last three digits, seven-four-two.","Wonderful, so it ends in seven-four-two. Thank you very much for your time, Miss Coleman, and we'll be in touch with you very soon."], Q:[{"q":"The surname the caller spells out.","a":"Coleman","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The creative role she has decided on.","a":"designer","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"How many years of professional design work she has done.","a":"3|three","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The month from which she would be completely free.","a":"August","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The salary figure she settles on after reconsidering.","a":"30000|30,000|thirty thousand","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"How many months of notice she must give.","a":"1|one","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The place where her full portfolio can be viewed.","a":"website","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The senior person who agreed to recommend her.","a":"manager","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The weekday reserved for first-round interviews.","a":"Tuesday","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The three numbers her contact line finishes with.","a":"742","lim":"A NUMBER"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Office tour", map:PLAN, intro:"a manager showing a new employee around the office floor plan", tr1:"Welcome, everyone, and thank you for coming in today. Let me talk you through the office floor plan so that you know where everything is before your first day. As you step in through the entrance, which is at the bottom middle of the plan, the reception desk is right beside you, just to the right of the entrance, so you really can't miss it as you arrive. Now let your eyes travel up to the top of the plan. In the very top left-hand corner you'll find the main meeting room, which is where we hold our larger presentations. Moving along the top row towards the middle, and specifically just to the right of centre, is the design studio, and that is the space where you graphic designers will actually be based, so do take note of it. Carry on to the very top right-hand corner and there you have the kitchen, which is handy for making yourself a cup of tea during your breaks. Now come back down to the bottom row of the plan. Over in the bottom left-hand corner sits the server room, which houses all of our computer equipment and is normally kept locked for security reasons. Let me pause there for a moment before I point out the remaining rooms.", tr2:"Right, let's finish off the layout. Back along the top row again, this time just to the left of centre, you'll see the manager's office, so it sits neatly between the meeting room in the corner and the design studio. Then, returning to the bottom row, the print room is located at the bottom of the plan just to the left of the entrance, so it's very close to reception but on the opposite side of the doorway. Finally, in the bottom right-hand corner, diagonally opposite the server room, you'll find the storeroom, where we keep all our stationery and spare supplies. That completes the layout of the rooms, so do take a moment to make sure you can picture where each one is before we move on. Now, a little background about the company itself. Some people assume we've been around since twenty ten, but that isn't quite right; the business was actually founded in twenty fifteen, so we're still a fairly young company. And one last thing about how we work here. Unlike many firms, we don't expect people to be at their desks from nine to five, nor do we ask staff to come in at weekends. Instead, most of our employees work flexible hours, choosing start and finish times that suit them, as long as the work gets done. I hope that gives you a clear picture, and welcome once again to the team.", Q:[{"q":"The desk where arriving visitors are first greeted.","a":"G"},{"q":"The room set aside for the larger presentations.","a":"A"},{"q":"The workspace where the graphic design staff will sit.","a":"C"},{"q":"The spot for preparing a hot drink during a break.","a":"D"},{"q":"The secured room housing all the computer hardware.","a":"E"},{"q":"The private office belonging to the person in charge.","a":"B"},{"q":"The room close to reception used for printing.","a":"F"},{"q":"The area holding stationery and spare supplies.","a":"H"},{"q":"In which year was the firm actually set up? A 2010 B 2015 C 2020","a":"B"},{"q":"How do the majority of staff organise their working day? A they choose flexible hours B they work from home C they come in at weekends","a":"A"}]},
  {n:3, title:"Two colleagues discuss a new project", sp:["Colleague A","Colleague B"], intro:"two colleagues discussing the plans for a new project", tr1:["So, I've been reading the brief for our new project, and I want to make sure I've understood it correctly. It's a mobile app we're building, isn't it, not a website?","That's right. At one point there was talk of doing a website, and someone even mentioned a game, but no, the plan is firmly a mobile app now.","Great, a mobile app it is. And who exactly are we building it for? Who's the main audience?","Well, it's not aimed at teachers, and it isn't for parents either, although both were suggested early on. It's really for students, they're our main users.","Students, understood. Now, what about money? Are we working with a healthy budget on this one?","Sadly not. I wish I could say it was large, or at least flexible, but the honest truth is that the budget is quite limited, so we'll have to be careful.","That's a shame, but good to know. And do we have a launch date yet? How long have we got?","We're not launching in three months, thankfully, and it's not as far off as twelve months either. The target is to launch in six months' time.","Six months, alright. Given all of that, what worries you the most about this project?","Honestly, it's not the budget that keeps me up at night, nor the size of the team, it's the deadlines, they're really very tight."], tr2:["Those tight deadlines make me think about people. Do we actually have enough staff, or will we need to bring someone new in?","We're a bit short, I'm afraid. We don't need another designer, and a writer wouldn't help us at this stage; what we really need is to hire a developer to handle the coding.","A developer, that makes sense. So where do we begin? What should our very first step be?","I know it's tempting to jump straight into coding, and some would say start with marketing, but no, our first step has to be research, properly understanding what students actually want.","Research first, I agree. And how often do you think we should get together to review our progress?","Meeting every day would be far too much, and once a month would be far too little. I'd suggest we meet weekly, that feels about right.","Weekly meetings, perfect. What about tracking all of our tasks? Should we use email, or maybe just keep notes on paper?","Email gets messy and paper gets lost, so let's avoid both. Let's use Trello for tracking the tasks, since everyone on the team already knows it.","Trello, good choice. And one last thing, when it comes to the big calls, who makes the final decisions? Is it the team, or the clients?","It's neither the whole team nor the clients in the end. Ultimately, the manager makes the final decisions, though of course they'll listen to our input first."], Q:[{"q":"What kind of product is the team going to build?","a":"B","o":["a website","a mobile application","a game"]},{"q":"Who are the intended main users of the product?","a":"C","o":["teachers","parents","learners"]},{"q":"How is the money available for the work described?","a":"A","o":["restricted","generous","adjustable"]},{"q":"When is the product scheduled to go live?","a":"B","o":["in three months","in half a year","in a year"]},{"q":"What does the speaker worry about most?","a":"C","o":["the funding","the size of the team","the time limits"]},{"q":"Which additional team member do they need to take on?","a":"A","o":["a coder","a graphic artist","a copywriter"]},{"q":"What ought to be their very first move?","a":"B","o":["writing code","carrying out research","promotion"]},{"q":"How often do they plan to review their progress together?","a":"C","o":["every day","every month","every week"]},{"q":"Which method will they use to keep track of tasks?","a":"A","o":["Trello","electronic mail","paper notes"]},{"q":"Who ultimately takes the important decisions?","a":"B","o":["the whole team","the manager","the customers"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: the psychology of teamwork", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below. Write the answer for each gap and keep strictly to the word or number limit shown.", layout:"flow", flow:["A strong team depends far more on working together than on individual {1}","Members must feel safe to speak up without fear, which is termed psychological {2}","The very best teams pass information around {3}, holding nothing back","A team drawn from varied backgrounds, that is {4}, widens the range of ideas despite some early friction","One clear, shared {5} keeps everybody moving in the same direction","Piling on people is risky, since very {6} teams frequently do worse","In big groups some members quietly stop helping, a problem called social {7}","For most tasks the ideal number is roughly {8} people","In healthy teams members listen at least as much as they {9}","A safe climate lets a person openly own up to a {10} and treat it as a lesson"], intro:"part of a university lecture about the psychology of teamwork", tr1:"Today's lecture concerns the psychology of teamwork, and in particular what really makes a team effective. Research shows that a good team is far more than a simple collection of talented individuals. In fact, how the members work together, their cooperation, matters more than raw ability. A group of brilliant experts who cannot cooperate will usually be beaten by a well-coordinated group of quite ordinary people. One of the most important findings concerns something that psychologists call psychological safety. This is the feeling that you can speak up, ask a question, or raise a concern without any fear of being judged or punished. Teams that score highly on psychological safety consistently perform better than those that do not. Closely related to this is communication. The very strongest teams share information openly, holding nothing back and keeping no secrets from one another. Another factor is diversity. When a team includes people from different backgrounds, that diversity brings a much wider range of ideas and perspectives, although it can admittedly cause a little friction in the early stages. Finally, and this may sound obvious, a team needs direction. A clear, shared goal keeps everyone pulling in the same direction and stops individuals drifting off to pursue their own private aims. Let me now turn to the important question of team size.", tr2:"So how big should a team actually be? This is where the research becomes really interesting. You might assume that the more people you add, the more a team can achieve, but studies tend to find the opposite. Very large teams often perform worse than smaller ones. There are two main reasons for this. First, coordination becomes far harder; with so many people involved, simply organising who does what eats up huge amounts of time. Second, in a big group some members quietly stop contributing, relying on everyone else to carry the load. Psychologists have a name for this problem: they call it social loafing. Because of these effects, the best size for most tasks is surprisingly small, often around five people, which tends to be large enough to cover the necessary skills yet small enough to stay tightly coordinated. Let me return briefly to communication as well, because it links back to size. In the best teams, members listen at least as much as they talk, so that even the quieter voices are genuinely heard. And this connects to psychological safety once more: in a healthy team, a member can openly admit a mistake, treating it as a chance to learn rather than something to hide. Get these ingredients right, and even a modest group of people can achieve genuinely remarkable things together.", Q:[{"q":"Cooperation counts for more than a member's raw ______.","a":"ability","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The sense that you may raise a concern unpunished is psychological ______.","a":"safety","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The finest teams exchange information ______.","a":"openly","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Having members of mixed backgrounds is known as team ______.","a":"diversity","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"A single agreed ______ stops people chasing their own aims.","a":"goal","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Teams that are very ______ tend to underperform.","a":"large","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"When people coast and let others carry them, it is called social ______.","a":"loafing","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The most effective group size is usually about ______.","a":"five|5","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Ideally members hear others out as much as they ______.","a":"talk","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"A secure atmosphere allows someone to confess a ______.","a":"mistake","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"Hillside Health Centre", blurb:"Patient registration · Health centre grounds · Health plan · How the heart works",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"New patient registration", sp:["Officer","Patient"], instr:"Complete the patient record table below. Write your answers in the gaps, keeping within the stated word limit for each.", layout:"table", table:[["Detail","Response"],["Family name","{1}"],["Birth month","{2}"],["Chosen doctor","Dr {3}"],["Purpose of appointment","a general {4}"],["Day booked","{5}"],["Start time","{6}"],["Item to bring in","a list of {7}"],["Known allergy","{8}"],["Person to contact in an emergency","{9}"],["How refills are requested","{10}"]], intro:"a conversation between a registration officer and a new patient at a health centre", tr1:["Good morning, you have reached Hillside Health Centre, the registration desk. How can I help you today?","Hello, I have just moved into the area and I would like to register as a new patient.","Of course, I can set that up over the phone now. Could I start with your surname, please?","Yes, it is Nguyen. That is often misspelt, so let me spell it. It is N-G-U-Y-E-N, Nguyen.","Thank you, I have that as N-G-U-Y-E-N. Now, could you tell me your month of birth?","I was born in the spring. My month of birth is March, the fifteenth of March to be precise.","Lovely, March it is. Do you have a preference for which doctor you would like to be registered with?","A friend recommended Doctor Bell, so if there is space on her list I would like to register with Doctor Bell, please.","Doctor Bell has room for new patients, so that is fine. And what is the reason for your first visit?","Nothing is wrong, really. I would just like a general check-up now that I have settled in.","A general check-up, noted. Let me look at Doctor Bell's diary. I can see she has some slots next week.","That would be great. Which day were you thinking of? I am fairly flexible this week.","How about Wednesday? She has a few openings that morning, so Wednesday would suit you best.","Wednesday works perfectly, thank you. Let us go with the Wednesday appointment."], tr2:["Now let me fix the time for that Wednesday. I could offer you quarter to ten — oh, sorry, let me correct that, quarter past ten, so ten fifteen in the morning.","Quarter past ten, ten fifteen, that is fine. Should I bring anything along with me to that first appointment?","Yes, please bring a list of any medication you are currently taking. A written list of all your medication really helps the doctor.","No problem, I will write out a full list of my medication and bring it with me on the day.","Wonderful. And an important safety question — do you have any allergies that we should record on your file?","Yes, I do. I am allergic to penicillin, so that definitely needs to go on my record.","Thank you, I have flagged penicillin as an allergy on your notes. Now, who should we list as your emergency contact?","You can put down my sister as my emergency contact. She lives nearby and is easy to reach.","Your sister, noted as emergency contact. Is there anything else you would like to know before we finish?","Actually, yes. Once I am registered, how do I go about getting my repeat prescriptions each month?","Good question. Repeat prescriptions can be ordered online through our website, which saves you queuing at the desk.","Ordering them online sounds very convenient. Thank you for setting all of this up for me today."], Q:[{"q":"The new patient's family name.","a":"Nguyen","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The month in which the patient was born.","a":"March","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The surname of the doctor the patient will be signed up with.","a":"Bell","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What kind of examination the patient wants at the first visit.","a":"check-up|checkup|check up","lim":"NO MORE THAN TWO WORDS"},{"q":"The weekday the appointment is arranged for.","a":"Wednesday","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The clock time the appointment will begin.","a":"10.15|10:15|quarter past ten","lim":"A TIME"},{"q":"What the patient is asked to bring written down for the doctor.","a":"medication|medicines","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The substance the patient reacts badly to.","a":"penicillin","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The family member named for emergencies.","a":"sister","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The method used to request monthly repeat prescriptions.","a":"online","lim":"ONE WORD"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Health centre grounds", map:PARK, intro:"a health centre worker describing a plan of the centre grounds", tr1:"Welcome, everyone. Let me talk you through this plan of the health centre grounds so that you can find your way around easily on your first visit. You enter the grounds at the bottom, right in the middle, and I will describe the buildings from there. Let us begin along the top row of the plan. The main clinic building, which is the largest and where most consultations take place, sits in the top left-hand corner. Moving to the right along that top row, just left of the centre, you will find the physiotherapy unit, where our physiotherapists help patients recover after injuries. Carrying on to the right, just right of the centre at the top, is the dental surgery, so if you have a dental appointment that is the place to head for. And finally, in the very top right-hand corner, you will see the pharmacy, where you collect any medicines that have been prescribed. Now let me come back down to the bottom row and start near where you came in. Remember that the entrance is at the bottom in the middle. Reception, where you should check in when you arrive, is positioned just to the right of the entrance, so you will see it almost immediately as you walk in. Please do check in there first before going anywhere else in the grounds.", tr2:"Let me continue with the rest of the bottom row so that you have the full picture. Over in the bottom left-hand corner you will find the blood test laboratory, which is where you go if your doctor has asked for any blood samples to be taken. Coming back towards the middle along the bottom, and this time just to the left of the entrance, is the waiting area, with plenty of comfortable seating for patients who are waiting to be called. So remember, the waiting area sits on the left of the entrance while reception is on the right. Filling the bottom right-hand corner is the car park, so if you have driven here today that is where you should leave your vehicle. That covers all of the buildings on the plan. Before I finish, a couple of practical points about visiting us. In terms of how busy we get, you might expect the weekends or Fridays to be the worst, but in fact the centre is by far at its busiest on Monday mornings, so do bear that in mind when booking. And one final request: we ask that all patients arrive a full ten minutes early for their appointments, not just on time and not merely five minutes before, so that there is enough time to check in calmly.", Q:[{"q":"Where is the largest building, used for most appointments, located?","a":"A"},{"q":"Where can patients pick up prescribed medicines?","a":"D"},{"q":"Where should someone go for a tooth appointment?","a":"C"},{"q":"Where do patients recovering from injuries receive treatment?","a":"B"},{"q":"Where should arriving patients register their presence?","a":"G"},{"q":"Where are blood samples taken?","a":"E"},{"q":"Where can patients sit while they wait to be called?","a":"F"},{"q":"Where should drivers leave their cars?","a":"H"},{"q":"When does the centre have the most patients?","a":"B","o":["at the weekend","early on Mondays","on Fridays"]},{"q":"How far ahead of their appointment are patients asked to turn up?","a":"C","o":["exactly on time","five minutes ahead","ten minutes ahead"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Nurse and patient set a health plan", sp:["Nurse","Patient"], intro:"a nurse and a patient discussing a personal health plan", tr1:["Right, let us sit down together and set some realistic health goals for you. To start with, what would you say is your main aim at the moment?","Well, I have thought about it, and although building muscle did cross my mind, what I really want most of all is to lose some weight.","Losing weight is a very sensible main goal, so let us build the plan around that. For exercise, I would steer you away from running, which can be hard on the knees. Swimming is what I would really recommend, because it is gentle on the joints.","Swimming sounds good, I have always enjoyed being in the water. How often should I be going to the pool?","Let us start you off at three times a week. Not once, which is too little to see any progress, and we can build up later, but three sessions weekly is the right number to begin with.","Three times a week, I can manage that. What about my eating? Where should I start with my diet?","The very first thing I would like you to cut is sugar. People often think of salt or fat first, but for you sugar is the one to reduce before anything else.","Cutting the sugar will be hard, but I will try. And is there anything about my sleep I should change?","Yes, sleep matters a great deal. Try to get a full eight hours each night. Six is really not enough, and even seven is a little short for you, so aim for eight hours.","Eight hours a night, I will do my best to get to bed earlier then."], tr2:["Now, there is one more habit I want to ask about. Do you smoke at all?","Yes, I am afraid I do. I have smoked for a few years now and I know it is not good for me.","I appreciate your honesty. Simply cutting down would help a little, but giving up smoking altogether should really be your top priority, more than the coffee or the odd glass of wine.","I understand. I will make quitting smoking the thing I focus on. Anything else you will keep an eye on?","Yes, we will check your blood pressure every month, so a monthly check rather than weekly or once a year.","A monthly blood pressure check, that is fine. Anything I should be adding to my meals rather than cutting?","Good question. I would like you to add more vegetables to every meal. Not extra meat or dairy, but plenty of vegetables on the plate.","More vegetables with every meal, understood. And is there any particular food I should stay away from?","Yes, please avoid fast food as much as you can. Fruit and fish are both fine, but fast food is the thing to keep away from.","I will cut out the fast food. When would you like me to come back?","Let us arrange a follow-up in six weeks. That is sooner than three months but gives you more time than a fortnight to progress.","Six weeks it is. Thank you so much for all of this advice today."], Q:[{"q":"What does the patient say is his chief objective?","a":"B","o":["gaining muscle","shedding some weight","easing tension"]},{"q":"Which activity does the nurse suggest as best?","a":"C","o":["jogging","cycling","swimming"]},{"q":"How many sessions each week does the nurse advise to begin with?","a":"B","o":["a single time","three times","five times"]},{"q":"Which item should the patient reduce before anything else?","a":"A","o":["sugar","salt","fat"]},{"q":"How much sleep should the patient aim for nightly?","a":"C","o":["six hours","seven hours","eight hours"]},{"q":"Which habit should be the patient's main thing to abandon?","a":"B","o":["drinking coffee","smoking","drinking alcohol"]},{"q":"How frequently will the patient's blood pressure be measured?","a":"A","o":["once a month","once a week","once a year"]},{"q":"What does the nurse want the patient to include more of at meals?","a":"C","o":["meat","dairy products","vegetables"]},{"q":"Which food is the patient told to keep away from?","a":"A","o":["fast food","fruit","fish"]},{"q":"When is the next appointment scheduled?","a":"B","o":["in a fortnight","in six weeks","in three months"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: how the human heart works", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below describing the heart. Fill each gap according to the word limit given for that answer.", layout:"flow", flow:["The heart is essentially a muscular {1}","It is only about as big as a clenched {2}","It contracts roughly one hundred thousand times every {3}","The upper pair of chambers are known as the {4}","The lower pair of chambers are known as the {5}","Blood takes on fresh oxygen inside the {6}","One-way {7} prevent blood from running backwards","Together the heart and vessels make up the {8} system","Doing {9} regularly makes the heart muscle stronger","Heart {10} is among the top causes of death across the globe"], intro:"a lecture about how the human heart works", tr1:"Good afternoon, everyone. In today's lecture we are going to examine how the human heart works, one of the most remarkable organs in the whole body. Let us begin with the basics. At its simplest, the heart is a muscular pump. That is the best way to picture it — a strong, muscular pump whose job is to push blood around the body without ever stopping. Despite doing such an enormous job, it is surprisingly small. The heart is roughly the size of a fist, your own clenched fist, sitting just behind and slightly to the left of the breastbone. Now, consider how hard this organ works. The heart never rests. It keeps beating, on average, around one hundred thousand times a day, every single day, throughout a person's entire life. That is an astonishing number when you stop to think about it. Let us now look inside. The heart is divided into four chambers. There are two upper chambers and two lower chambers. The two upper chambers are called the atria — that is a-t-r-i-a, atria — and they receive blood as it comes back into the heart. Directly below them sit the two lower chambers, and these are called the ventricles. The ventricles are more muscular because they do the powerful work of pushing blood out again.", tr2:"So how does the blood actually move through all of this? Let us follow its journey. Blood that is low in oxygen is first pumped from the heart to the lungs. It is inside the lungs that the blood collects fresh oxygen, and once it has done so it returns to the heart to be pumped out to the rest of the body. To keep everything flowing in the correct direction, the heart contains a series of one-way valves sitting between the chambers. These valves stop the blood from flowing backwards, and it is the opening and closing of the valves that produces that familiar heartbeat sound you can hear through a stethoscope. Taken all together, the heart and the network of blood vessels are known as the circulatory system, because it keeps blood circulating continuously. Finally, a word about keeping this system healthy. Regular exercise strengthens the heart muscle, making it a more efficient pump, whereas a poor diet can gradually clog the vessels and lead to illness. Indeed, heart disease remains one of the leading causes of death worldwide, and that is precisely why doctors place such strong emphasis on prevention. In our next session we will look more closely at how best to protect the heart over a lifetime.", Q:[{"q":"The heart works essentially as a muscular what?","a":"pump","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The heart is roughly the same size as a clenched what?","a":"fist","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The heart contracts about one hundred thousand times per what?","a":"day","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What name is given to the two upper chambers?","a":"atria","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What name is given to the two lower chambers?","a":"ventricles","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"In which organ does blood pick up oxygen?","a":"lungs","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What one-way structures keep blood from flowing the wrong way?","a":"valves","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The heart and blood vessels together are called the what system?","a":"circulatory","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Doing what on a regular basis strengthens the heart muscle?","a":"exercise","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Heart what is one of the leading causes of death worldwide?","a":"disease","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"Riverfest Music Festival", blurb:"Ticket booking · Festival site map · Festival plan · Music & the brain",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Ticket booking", sp:["Officer","Caller"], instr:"Complete the booking table below. Write the answer for each gap using the word limit shown in brackets.", layout:"table", table:[["Detail","Information"],["Customer family name","{1}"],["Kind of pass chosen","a {2} pass"],["Passes required","{3}"],["Cost of one pass","£{4}"],["Sleeping arrangement","group will bring their own {5}"],["Day the group turns up","{6}"],["Reduction they qualify for","a {7} discount"],["Payment made today","only a {8}"],["Where passes are picked up","at the {9}"],["How the booking is confirmed","by {10} message"]], intro:"a telephone conversation between a festival ticket officer and a caller booking tickets", tr1:["Good morning, you've reached the Riverfest ticket line. My name's Daniel and I'll be helping you today. What can I do for you?","Hi there. I'd like to book some tickets for the festival this year, please. A friend went last summer and said it was wonderful, so a group of us decided we simply had to go.","That's great to hear. I can take all your details over the phone right now. Let me start with your surname, if that's alright.","Of course. It's Osborne. That's O-S-B-O-R-N-E. People often want to add an extra letter or spell it with a U, but there isn't one, it's just Osborne.","Lovely, I've got that written down. Now, we offer two kinds of ticket, a day pass and a weekend pass. Which of those would suit you best?","I did think about a day ticket at first, just to keep the cost down, but honestly we want the full experience, so make it a weekend one, please.","A weekend ticket it is, then. And how many of them will you be needing altogether?","There are four of us going, so four tickets, please. It's me and three friends from university.","Four weekend passes, noted. Just so you know the pricing before we go on, the day tickets are fifty pounds, but the weekend ones are eighty-five pounds each. Will your group be camping on site?","Yes, we will. We're bringing a tent and planning to stay right there for the whole weekend rather than travelling back and forth each day."], tr2:["Perfect, there's plenty of room in the camping field. When are you thinking of arriving? A lot of people come on the Thursday evening to settle in early.","We did look at the Thursday, but two of us have lectures that day, so we can't make Thursday. We'll come on Friday instead, hopefully by early afternoon. Oh, are there any discounts available?","There is, actually. There's a student discount if everyone can show a valid student ID at the gate. Since your group's from university, that should apply to all four of you.","Brilliant, we've all got our student cards on us, so that works perfectly. That'll save us a fair bit of money.","It certainly will. Now, would you like to pay in full today, or just put down a deposit to secure the tickets for now?","Money's a little tight before payday, so let's just do a deposit for now, and we'll settle the rest closer to the date.","No problem at all, a deposit it is. I'll hold the booking for you. One thing to note, we don't post physical tickets out any more these days.","Oh, right. So how do we actually get hold of them, then?","You'll collect the tickets at the gate when you arrive, just give your surname and show your ID there. And we'll send a confirmation through by text to the mobile number on the booking.","That's great, thank you so much for all your help. I'll keep an eye out for that text message closer to the time."], Q:[{"q":"The caller spells out her family name as","a":"Osborne","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Rather than a single-day option, the group opts for this pass type","a":"weekend","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Total quantity of passes the caller wants","a":"4|four","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Amount charged for each pass","a":"85|eighty-five","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Item of equipment the group will set up to sleep in on the field","a":"tent","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Since some have classes on Thursday, they will show up on this day instead","a":"Friday","lim":"A DATE"},{"q":"Because they all attend university, they are entitled to this category of reduction","a":"student","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"To hold the booking, they hand over this part-payment for now","a":"deposit","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Tickets are no longer posted, so they are handed over at this location on arrival","a":"gate","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The booking confirmation will arrive through this form of communication","a":"text","lim":"ONE WORD"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Festival site", map:STREET, intro:"a festival organiser describing the layout of the festival site to visitors", tr1:"Right everyone, gather round and I'll walk you through the festival site map so that nobody gets themselves lost this weekend. As you can see, you enter the whole site at the bottom, right in the centre, where it's marked entrance. Let me take you through the main landmarks one at a time. Let's begin with the biggest attraction of all, the main stage. That sits right up in the top left-hand corner of the map, so it's diagonally across the whole site from where you come in. Next, the food court. Some people assume the food is somewhere near the entrance, but it isn't, the food court is over in the top right-hand corner, as far along the top and as far to the right as you can possibly go. Now for the camping area, which is where most of you will be sleeping. That takes up the entire bottom right-hand corner of the site, directly below the food court. Coming back in towards the middle, the first aid tent is very easy to find, it sits just to the left of the entrance, so as you walk in it'll be immediately on your left-hand side. And finally for this first group, the toilets. You'll find the toilets tucked away down in the bottom left-hand corner, over on the far left of the site as you look at the map, well away from the food.", tr2:"Now let me point out the rest of the site so that you've got the full picture in your heads. Along the top of the map, in between the main stage and the food court, there are two more important spots. Just to the left of centre along the top you'll see the second stage, so it sits directly to the right of the main stage. Then just to the right of centre, still along that top edge, is the information tent, which is the place to head for if you have any questions during the weekend. Back down at the bottom now, right next to the entrance, the car park is just to the right of the entrance, so as you come in it'll be immediately on your right, sitting directly opposite the first aid tent. A couple of final notes before you all head off. People often ask us when the main act is playing. Well, it's not the Friday and it's not the Sunday, the main act performs on the Saturday night, so do make sure you're back at the main stage in good time that evening. And one important rule about what you can bring in. Cameras are absolutely fine, and outside food is allowed too, so feel free to pack your snacks. However, glass bottles are strictly not permitted anywhere on the site, for everyone's safety, so please pour any drinks into plastic before you arrive. Enjoy the festival.", Q:[{"q":"The principal performance stage, sitting diagonally opposite the way in, up in the far top-left corner","a":"A"},{"q":"The area selling meals, placed as far to the top and right as the site allows","a":"D"},{"q":"The zone where most people will pitch tents, filling the whole bottom-right corner beneath the eating area","a":"H"},{"q":"The medical point, positioned immediately to the left as you walk through the entrance","a":"F"},{"q":"The washrooms, hidden away in the far bottom-left corner, well apart from where food is served","a":"E"},{"q":"The smaller performance platform, sitting just left of centre along the top, right beside the main stage","a":"B"},{"q":"The help desk for queries, located a little to the right of centre along the upper edge","a":"C"},{"q":"The parking area, found directly to the right of the way in and facing the medical point","a":"G"},{"q":"The evening on which the star performer takes to the stage is","a":"B","o":["Friday","Saturday evening","Sunday"]},{"q":"The one item that visitors are banned from bringing onto the grounds is","a":"C","o":["cameras","snacks brought from outside","bottles made of glass"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Two friends plan the festival", sp:["Friend A","Friend B"], intro:"two friends discussing their plans for a weekend music festival", tr1:["So, are you getting excited for the festival next weekend? I can hardly believe it's finally almost here.","I can't wait, it's all I've been thinking about. What are you most hoping to catch there?","The pop acts look fun, and the jazz musicians are meant to be brilliant too, but honestly, for me it's all about the rock bands, that's what I'm going for.","Same here, completely. The rock line-up is the whole reason I bought a ticket. Right, where shall the two of us meet before we set off?","I did wonder about the gate, or even here at my home, but the simplest thing is to meet at the station, since we're both passing through it anyway.","Good thinking, the station it is. And we're still travelling by train, aren't we? I know some people are driving.","A couple of friends offered a lift by car, and there's a coach some are taking, but the train's easiest by far and drops us right nearby, so yes, let's go by train.","Train sorted. Now, what should we pack? The weather's been so changeable lately.","I checked the forecast this morning and it looks pretty wet, so definitely bring a raincoat. A sunhat would just be wishful thinking at this point.","Ha, true. A raincoat it is. And how much should we set aside for food each day?","Let's budget twenty pounds a day each. I've seen the prices, and thirty or even fifty would be far more than we'll actually get through."], tr2:["Twenty pounds a day sounds sensible. Out of everyone playing, which single act must we not miss?","Without a doubt the headliner on the Saturday night. I'd happily skip a DJ set or the second stage to be right at the front for that, but the headliner is non-negotiable.","Agreed, we'll get there early. I have to say, my one real worry is the crowds, it always gets so packed near the front.","The cost crossed my mind, and the rain too, but you're right, the crowds are the thing to watch out for. We should agree a meeting spot in case we get separated.","Speaking of which, what if our phones die in all of that? Mine never lasts a full day.","If our phones run flat, we can charge them at the information tent, they've got a charging point there. Not the food court or the first aid tent, I checked, it's the information tent.","Brilliant, the information tent it is. So when do we actually head home afterwards?","Not the Friday, and I'd rather not rush off on the Saturday, so let's stay right through and travel back on the Sunday, once it's all wrapped up.","Sunday works for me. One last thing, to save space and money, shall we share a tent rather than bring one each?","Definitely, let's share one tent. No point carrying two along, and it'll be warmer that way anyway. I'll dig mine out of the loft tonight."], Q:[{"q":"The style of music both friends are keenest to hear is","a":"B","o":["chart pop","rock","jazz"]},{"q":"The place the two of them have agreed to meet up beforehand is","a":"A","o":["the railway station","the entrance gate","one of their houses"]},{"q":"To reach the festival they have decided to go by","a":"C","o":["coach","a friend's car","train"]},{"q":"Given the forecast, the item they intend to pack is a","a":"B","o":["sun hat","waterproof coat","warm blanket"]},{"q":"The amount they plan to allow themselves for meals each day is","a":"A","o":["£20","£30","£50"]},{"q":"The one act they both insist on being there for is","a":"C","o":["the second stage line-up","a DJ performance","the top billed act"]},{"q":"The thing that concerns them the most about the event is the","a":"B","o":["wet weather","large crowds","expense"]},{"q":"If their phones run out of power, they can recharge them at","a":"A","o":["the information point","the medical tent","the food area"]},{"q":"The day they have chosen to make their way back home is","a":"C","o":["Friday","Saturday","Sunday"]},{"q":"To cut down on space and cost, they have decided to share a","a":"B","o":["taxi ride","single tent","meal"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: music and the brain", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below by filling each numbered gap. Obey the word limit given in brackets for every answer.", layout:"flow", flow:["HOW MUSIC AFFECTS US","Uniquely, listening engages nearly the entire {1} at the same time","down to","Enjoyable music prompts the brain to release {2}, the reward chemical","down to","It measurably lowers {3} and even reduces blood pressure","down to","In rehabilitation a steady beat helps stroke patients regain {4} in their limbs","down to","In the classroom it can strengthen {5} for certain students","ACROSS THE LIFESPAN","Even days-old infants instinctively react to a {6}","down to","Daily practice on an instrument gradually raises a child's {7}","down to","For those with {8}, a familiar tune can bring back lost memories","down to","Singing together fosters social {9} among strangers","down to","Overall, the impact of music on mood is strongly {10}"], intro:"a university lecture about the effects of music on the human brain", tr1:"Good afternoon everyone. Today's lecture looks at the remarkable effect that music has on the human brain, and I think you'll be surprised at how far-reaching it turns out to be. Let's begin with something quite extraordinary. Unlike most activities, which light up only a small region, listening to music activates almost the whole brain at once. Brain scans show activity spreading right across it, from the areas that handle sound to those involved in memory, emotion and movement. It really is one of the very few things that engages the entire brain simultaneously. So why does music feel so good to us? The answer lies in chemistry. When we hear music we enjoy, the brain triggers the release of dopamine, the same chemical linked to pleasure and reward, the one released when we eat a favourite meal. That rush of dopamine is a large part of why a great song can give you actual shivers. Beyond pleasure, music has clear, measurable effects on the body too. Studies consistently show that it can reduce stress, calming us after a difficult day and even lowering our blood pressure. That is precisely why hospitals and dental surgeries so often play gentle music in their waiting rooms. The benefits reach deep into medicine as well. In rehabilitation, therapists use rhythmic music to help stroke patients recover movement in their arms and legs, since a steady beat helps the brain re-learn how to coordinate the limbs. And in the classroom, background music has been shown to improve memory in some students, helping certain facts stick more firmly in the mind.", tr2:"Now let me turn to how these effects change across our whole lives, from the very youngest to the very oldest. It begins astonishingly early. Even newborn babies, only days old, respond instinctively to rhythm, moving their tiny bodies and settling when a regular beat is played, long before they could understand a single word. As children grow, actively making music matters even more than simply listening. Learning to play an instrument, whether the piano or the violin, gradually boosts concentration and discipline over the years, because practising every day trains the mind to focus and to stick at a difficult task. The benefits stretch right to the other end of life, as well. Music therapy is increasingly used to help people living with dementia, and it can be deeply moving to watch, because a familiar old song will often revive memories that had seemed lost completely, letting someone reconnect with their past. Music is also a profoundly social thing. When people take part in group singing, whether in a choir or around a campfire, it builds a strong sense of social bonding, drawing strangers together and making them feel part of something shared. So, to draw all this together, from the newborn to the elderly, from the hospital ward to the concert hall, the evidence points firmly in one direction. Whatever else it does, the overall effect of music on our mood is overwhelmingly positive, and that, above all, is why it matters so much. Thank you.", Q:[{"q":"Rather than one small region, music switches on almost the entire","a":"brain","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Music we like causes the brain to give off this pleasure-related substance","a":"dopamine","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"One measurable bodily effect is that music brings down levels of","a":"stress","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Therapists use rhythm to help stroke sufferers get back this ability in their arms and legs","a":"movement","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Played in the background, music has been found to sharpen this in some learners","a":"memory","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Newborns react instinctively to a regular","a":"rhythm","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Learning an instrument steadily improves a young person's focus, or","a":"concentration","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Music therapy is used more and more to support people living with","a":"dementia","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Communal singing creates a powerful sense of social","a":"bonding","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The lecturer concludes that music's overall influence on our mood is overwhelmingly","a":"positive","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"Green Lettings", blurb:"Rental enquiry · Apartment building plan · Flatmates · History of housing",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Rental enquiry", sp:["Officer","Caller"], instr:"Complete the table below. Write ONE WORD AND/OR A NUMBER for each answer unless a different limit is shown.", layout:"table", table:[["Detail","Caller's response"],["Family name","{1}"],["Kind of property sought","{2}"],["Number of rooms for sleeping","{3}"],["District wanted","city {4}"],["Most she will pay monthly","£{5}"],["Earliest possible move-in","{6}"],["Sum needed as security","£{7}"],["Prefers the place to come","{8}"],["Keeps any animals","{9}"],["When she would rather be phoned","{10}"]], intro:"a telephone conversation between an officer at a lettings agency and a caller enquiring about renting a property", tr1:["Good morning, Green Lettings, this is the rental office, how can I help you today?","Hello, yes, I'm looking to rent somewhere, and a friend of mine recommended your agency, so I thought I'd give you a call.","Lovely, I can certainly help you with that. Let me just take a few details first. Could I start with your surname, please?","Of course. It's Fischer. Let me spell that for you, it's F-I-S-C-H-E-R. People often write it with an 's-h' by mistake, but it's with a 'c-h'.","Thank you, Fischer, F-I-S-C-H-E-R, I've got that. And are you looking for a house or a flat?","Well, I did wonder about a small house at first, but honestly a flat would suit me a great deal better, so let's say a flat, please.","A flat it is, then. And how many bedrooms were you hoping for?","I thought about just the one to keep the cost down, but I really do need a spare room for guests, so two bedrooms would be ideal.","Two bedrooms, noted. And which area of town would you prefer to be in?","I did look at the suburbs, but the long commute put me right off, so the city centre, ideally, if there's anything available there.","The city centre, right you are. And what would your maximum rent be each month?","I could stretch up to a thousand at a push, but realistically I'd want to keep it to nine hundred pounds a month."], tr2:["Nine hundred a month, understood. And when were you hoping to move in?","As soon as I can, really. I did say September in an earlier email, but my current lease runs on a little longer, so October is when I can actually move.","October, that gives us plenty of time to sort things out. Now, I should mention the deposit. Let me just check the figure, it's one thousand, sorry, that's the old rate, it's twelve hundred pounds now.","Twelve hundred pounds for the deposit, all right, I can manage that.","Great. And would you want the flat furnished or unfurnished?","I don't own much furniture yet, so furnished would be far easier for me, yes, furnished please.","Furnished, noted. And do you have any pets? Some of our landlords are quite strict about that sort of thing.","No, no pets at all, so that shouldn't be a problem for anyone.","Perfect, that opens up rather more options for you. And finally, when's the best time for me to call you back once I've found a few listings?","I'm at work right through the day, and the mornings are hectic, so the evening is definitely the best time to reach me.","The evening, wonderful. I'll be in touch very soon with some suitable flats. Thanks for calling us today."], Q:[{"q":"How the caller's last name is spelt","a":"Fischer","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The style of home she finally chooses","a":"flat","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"How many rooms for sleeping she requires","a":"2|two","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The part of the city she settles on","a":"centre|center","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The top figure she is prepared to pay in rent","a":"900|nine hundred","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The month she can genuinely relocate","a":"October","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The amount required up front as a bond","a":"1200|twelve hundred|1,200","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Whether she wants furniture provided or not","a":"furnished","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Her reply about owning pets","a":"no|none","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The part of the day that suits her for a return call","a":"evening","lim":"ONE WORD"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Apartment building (ground floor)", map:PLAN, intro:"a letting agent describing the ground floor plan of an apartment building", tr1:"Right, let me talk you through the ground floor plan of the building, and it helps to picture the layout as two rows of rooms with a corridor running between them. You come in through the main entrance, which is at the bottom, right in the centre of the plan. As soon as you step inside, the lift is right in front of you, positioned just to the right of the entrance on the lower row, so you really can't miss it. Now look up to the very top of the plan. In the top left-hand corner is Flat 1, which is a studio flat, the smallest unit we have. Directly across from it, in the top right-hand corner, you'll find the laundry room, where the shared washing machines are kept. Coming back down to the lower row, the bin store sits in the bottom right-hand corner, tucked away at the far end so the smell doesn't bother anyone. And over on the opposite side, in the bottom left-hand corner, is the bike storage, where residents can chain up their bicycles. So along the bottom row, reading from the left, you begin with the bike storage in that far left corner, and the bin store is diagonally opposite it, over in the far right corner. Keep those four points fixed in your mind and the rest of the plan will fall into place nicely.", tr2:"Now for the remaining rooms on this floor. Go back to the main entrance at the bottom centre. We said the lift is just to the right of it. Well, just to the left of the entrance is the manager's office, so the manager can keep an eye on everyone who comes and goes. Then look again at the top row, along the top of the plan. We've already placed Flat 1 up in that top left corner. Moving inwards, just left of the centre along the top is Flat 2, and immediately beside it, just right of the centre along the top, is Flat 3, with the laundry room finishing the row over in the top right corner. So the top row, reading from left to right, runs Flat 1, then Flat 2, then Flat 3, and then the laundry. A couple of general points before we move on. People often assume a block like this has four floors, and some even think as many as eight, but in fact this building has six floors in total, so you're roughly in the middle if you live on the third. And a word about the bills. The rent does not cover electricity, and there's no internet included either, so you'll arrange those yourself, but the good news is that the rent does include your water, which is one less thing to worry about each month.", Q:[{"q":"Whereabouts is the elevator located","a":"G"},{"q":"Which spot holds the single-room studio (Flat 1)","a":"A"},{"q":"Where are the shared washing facilities","a":"D"},{"q":"In which corner is the rubbish area","a":"H"},{"q":"Where may residents leave their bicycles","a":"E"},{"q":"Which room does the caretaker use as an office","a":"F"},{"q":"Where can Flat 2 be found","a":"B"},{"q":"Which position marks Flat 3","a":"C"},{"q":"Altogether the block rises to:","a":"B","o":["four storeys","six storeys","eight storeys"]},{"q":"One utility already covered by the rent is:","a":"C","o":["the electricity supply","the broadband","the water"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Two flatmates discuss moving in", sp:["Flatmate A","Flatmate B"], intro:"two flatmates discussing the arrangements for moving into a new flat together", tr1:["Okay, so we've finally been offered the flat, that's brilliant, but there's loads to sort out. When do we actually move in?","Well, the agent first mentioned the first of September, and I did wonder about waiting until November, but the tenancy actually starts on the first of October, so that's the day we move in.","The first of October, great. Now the big one, how do we split the rent?","Some people divide it up by how much they earn, and others by room size, but I think the fairest way is to split it equally, straight down the middle, fifty-fifty.","Equally sounds fair to me. But hang on, the two bedrooms are quite different sizes, isn't that a bit unfair?","Good point. So we share the rent equally as a base, but whoever takes the bigger room pays a little extra on top, so it comes down to whoever's willing to pay more getting the larger room.","That makes sense, the bigger room goes to whoever pays more for it. Right, the flat's completely empty, so what should we buy first?","I did think about a bed frame, and we'll need a kitchen table eventually, but honestly the very first thing we should get is a sofa, so we've somewhere comfortable to sit.","A sofa first, agreed. And what about the bills, are we sharing the internet?","The water's already included in the rent, and we'll each buy our own food separately, but yes, the one bill we'll definitely share the cost of is the internet, split down the middle."], tr2:["Sounds good. Now, cleaning, we really should agree a rota before we fall out over it.","Definitely. I couldn't face doing it daily, and once a month would let it get filthy, so let's clean weekly, taking it in turns each week.","Weekly, taking turns, perfect. And what's our rule going to be on having guests over?","I don't want to say guests are banned, that's no fun, but I'd hate people just turning up unannounced either, so let's say guests are fine as long as we give each other a bit of notice first.","Fair enough, guests allowed as long as we give notice. And where are we going to park the car?","I asked the agent about that. There's no garage, and it isn't one of those places with underground parking either, so we'll just have to park on the street out front.","On the street it is, then. Honestly, my main worry isn't the parking, or even the money, and the rooms are a decent size, it's the noise, because that road is so incredibly busy.","Yes, the noise is the one thing that might really get to us, the traffic never seems to stop out there. Anyway, when do we go in and sign the contract?","The agent offered us Friday, and Monday was another option, but we both said Saturday suited us best, so let's go in and sign on Saturday."], Q:[{"q":"The tenancy formally begins on:","a":"B","o":["the first day of September","the first day of October","the first day of November"]},{"q":"They decide to divide the rent:","a":"A","o":["into two even shares","according to how big each room is","in line with what each person earns"]},{"q":"The larger bedroom is given to:","a":"C","o":["whichever of them is older","neither of them","the one prepared to pay extra"]},{"q":"The item they agree to purchase before anything else is:","a":"B","o":["a bed","a settee","a dining table"]},{"q":"The one expense they intend to split is:","a":"A","o":["the broadband","the water charge","their groceries"]},{"q":"They plan to do the cleaning:","a":"C","o":["every day","once a month","once a week"]},{"q":"Their agreed policy on visitors is that they are:","a":"B","o":["forbidden altogether","fine provided advance warning is given","welcome at any moment"]},{"q":"They will leave the car:","a":"A","o":["out on the road","inside a garage","in a basement car park"]},{"q":"The thing that troubles the speaker most is the:","a":"C","o":["expense","lack of room","sound from outside"]},{"q":"They arrange to put their signatures on the agreement this coming:","a":"B","o":["Friday","Saturday","Monday"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: history of housing", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below. Write ONE WORD ONLY for each answer.", layout:"flow", flow:["The first people had no way of making homes, so they took shelter inside {1}","Once crops and livestock removed the need to roam, families put up their first lasting {2}","In Roman times even ordinary people often lived in tall {3} of several floors","During the Middle Ages the typical dwelling was constructed from {4}, which made fire a real hazard","As factories pulled workers in, the towns grew badly {5}","After the wars, states threw up towering blocks of {6} to house many families cheaply","Today's building emphasises {7} efficiency through insulation, glazing and solar panels","A key difficulty now is a serious {8} of homes people can afford","The obvious remedy is {9} a lot more housing than at present","Looking forward, dwellings are predicted to become {10}, run automatically by technology"], intro:"part of a university lecture on the history of housing", tr1:"Good afternoon everyone. Today I want to trace how human housing has changed across the whole span of history, because where and how we live tells us a great deal about our societies. Let's begin at the very beginning. The earliest humans had no means to construct their own dwellings, and instead they simply sheltered in caves, using these natural rock formations for protection from the weather and from wild animals. Those caves served as home for tens of thousands of years. Everything changed, though, when farming began. Once people learned to grow crops and keep animals, they no longer had to wander in search of food, and so, for the very first time, they built permanent settlements, clusters of homes where the same families stayed year after year. From those first settlements grew villages, towns and eventually great cities. The Romans in particular were remarkably advanced. Their cities were surprisingly modern in feel, and ordinary citizens, not only the wealthy, often lived in tall, multi-storey apartments stacked several floors high, much like the blocks we know today. Move forward to the medieval period, and the picture changes again. In those centuries most ordinary houses were built of wood, since timber was cheap and easy to find, but that had one terrible drawback, as it made fire a constant danger. Then came the industrial revolution, when factories drew huge numbers of workers into the cities, and as a result those cities became terribly crowded, with far too many people packed into far too little space.", tr2:"Now let's turn to the twentieth century and beyond. Faced with rapidly growing populations after the wars, many governments needed to house large numbers of people quickly and cheaply, and their answer was to build tall blocks of flats, high-rise towers that could accommodate hundreds of families on a small footprint of land. These flats reshaped the skyline of nearly every major city. In more recent decades, the priorities of house-building have shifted once again. Modern housing increasingly focuses on energy efficiency, with thick insulation, better windows and solar panels, all designed to cut both bills and carbon emissions. Yet for all this progress, a serious difficulty remains. In a great many cities today, the central problem is a shortage of affordable homes, meaning there are simply not enough places that ordinary people can afford to rent or buy. The obvious solution, of course, is building far more housing than we currently do, though this is easier said than done, since suitable land in city centres is increasingly scarce and expensive. So what does the future hold? Well, looking ahead, homes are widely expected to become smart, that is, controlled automatically by technology, so that heating, lighting and security all adjust themselves to our needs without us lifting a finger. And on that note, we'll pause there and pick up the discussion next week.", Q:[{"q":"Where the earliest people sheltered","a":"caves","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The lasting communities that farming produced","a":"settlements","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The multi-floor homes common in Roman cities","a":"apartments","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The cheap material used for medieval houses","a":"wood","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What the industrial cities became as workers arrived","a":"crowded","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The type of tall block put up in the twentieth century","a":"flats","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The kind of efficiency modern housing aims for","a":"energy","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The present-day lack of affordable homes","a":"shortage","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The action offered as the answer to the housing problem","a":"building","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What future homes are expected to be","a":"smart","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"Sunseeker Travel", blurb:"Holiday booking · Resort map · Holiday plan · Tourism impacts",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Holiday booking", sp:["Agent","Caller"], instr:"Complete the booking table below. Write the exact word, number or figure you hear for each gap, keeping within the stated word limit for every answer.", layout:"table", table:[["Booking detail","Information given"],["Customer family name","{1}"],["Country chosen for the trip","{2}"],["Length of the stay","{3} days"],["Time of year for travelling","{4}"],["Total in the travelling group","{5}"],["Quality of accommodation","{6} star"],["Meals arrangement","{7} board"],["Maximum spend for each traveller","£{8}"],["Cover for the trip","{9}"],["Departure airport","{10}"]], intro:"a telephone conversation between a travel agent and a customer booking a holiday", tr1:["Good morning, Sunseeker Travel, how can I help you today?","Hello, I'd like to book a holiday for the summer, please.","Of course, I can help you with that. Could I take your surname to start the booking?","Yes, it's Alvarez. Let me spell that for you: A-L-V-A-R-E-Z, Alvarez.","Thank you very much. And whereabouts were you thinking of travelling to?","We'd love somewhere warm in the Mediterranean. I did wonder about Spain, but we went there last year, so we've settled on Greece this time.","Greece is a wonderful choice, very popular in the summer. And how long would you like to go for?","I was thinking a week at first, but no, let's make it ten days so we can really relax and unwind properly.","Ten days it is, then. And which month would suit you best for travelling?","We'd like to travel in July, while the children are off school for the holidays.","Lovely, July is a beautiful time to visit. And how many people will be travelling altogether?","There'll be three of us in total, myself, my partner and our daughter.","Perfect, three travelling. And how old is your daughter, if I may ask, as some of our hotels offer reduced rates for children?","She has just turned eight, so a child rate would be very welcome if there happens to be one on this particular trip, please."], tr2:["Now, what standard of hotel would you like? We have three, four and five star options available.","Four star would be perfect for us, comfortable and pleasant but not too extravagant or expensive.","A very sensible choice. And what about the board arrangement while you are staying there?","Half board, please, so breakfast and dinner are included, but we can still go out and explore for lunch.","That works nicely. May I ask roughly what your budget is per person for the trip?","Ideally I'd like to keep it under six hundred, but honestly about seven hundred pounds per person is fine if it means a nicer hotel.","Understood, so around seven hundred pounds each. Would you like to add travel insurance to the booking?","Yes, please include insurance. I'd never dream of travelling abroad without it, so definitely add it in.","Very wise. And finally, which airport would you like to fly from?","We'll fly from Manchester, as it's the closest to us. We did consider Birmingham, but Manchester is far more convenient for the family.","Manchester, noted. And would you prefer a room with a sea view, by the way? It is only a small extra charge per night.","Oh, yes please, a sea view would be lovely after a long day out, so do add that on for us.","Wonderful, that's everything noted down at my end. I'll put all of that together for you and send a confirmation email across shortly.","Thank you so much for all your help, that's been really easy and painless."], Q:[{"q":"The traveller gives her family name as:","a":"Alvarez","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Rather than Spain, the family has decided to holiday in:","a":"Greece","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"They finally opt to stay for this many days:","a":"10|ten","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The month during the school break when they wish to fly out:","a":"July","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The size of the party heading off together:","a":"3|three","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The grade of hotel they settle on:","a":"4|four","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The catering option covering breakfast and evening meals:","a":"half","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The amount each person is willing to spend on the trip:","a":"700|seven hundred","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Regarding cover against mishaps abroad, she asks for it to be:","a":"included|yes","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The airport nearest home that they choose to leave from:","a":"Manchester","lim":"ONE WORD"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Holiday resort", map:PARK, intro:"a resort representative describing a holiday resort map to a group of new guests", tr1:"Welcome, everyone, and let me talk you through the resort map so you can find your way around easily. You will see that you arrive at the bottom of the map, in the centre, where the main entrance is. As you come through that entrance, the reception desk is just to the right of it, so do please check in there first. There is a wide corridor running right across the middle of the resort, separating the lower buildings from the upper ones. Now let me take you up to the top row of the map. Right up in the top left-hand corner you will find the swimming pool, which is heated and open all day long. Immediately beside the pool, just to the left of centre along the top, is the kids' club, where our staff run games and activities for the younger guests. Carry on across the top and, just to the right of centre, you come to the restaurant, where all of your evening meals will be served. And finally, tucked away in the top right-hand corner, at the opposite end from the swimming pool, is the spa, which offers massages and treatments by appointment. So that is the whole of the top row, running from the pool on the left across to the spa on the right.", tr2:"Now let us come back down to the lower row of the map, below that central corridor. Down in the bottom left-hand corner you will find the gym, which is open twenty-four hours a day for any guests who like to keep fit. Moving along the bottom towards the middle, just to the left of the main entrance, is the bar, so it sits directly opposite the reception desk, which, as I mentioned, is on the right of the entrance. The bar serves drinks and light snacks throughout the afternoon and evening. Then, over on the far side, in the bottom right-hand corner, is the path down to the beach, so head for that corner whenever you fancy a swim in the sea. A couple of practical notes before I finish. Breakfast is served every morning in the restaurant, and please do remember that it stops at ten o'clock sharp, so it is not available only until nine, nor as late as eleven, ten in the morning is your cut-off. And you will be pleased to hear that the Wi-Fi is completely free right across the whole resort. You do not pay a penny for it, and it is not limited to the lobby either, so you can get online anywhere, in your room or out by the pool.", Q:[{"q":"The check-in desk where guests register on arrival is located at:","a":"G"},{"q":"The heated open-air bathing area that stays open all day is at:","a":"A"},{"q":"The supervised play area with games for younger guests is at:","a":"B"},{"q":"The venue serving the evening meals is found at:","a":"C"},{"q":"The wellness centre offering massages and treatments by appointment is at:","a":"D"},{"q":"The round-the-clock fitness suite for keeping in shape is at:","a":"E"},{"q":"The lounge serving drinks and light snacks in the afternoon and evening is at:","a":"F"},{"q":"The walkway leading down to the seashore is at:","a":"H"},{"q":"The morning meal is available no later than:","a":"B","o":["9 in the morning","10 in the morning","11 in the morning"]},{"q":"Internet access across the resort is best described as:","a":"A","o":["available at no cost","charged for","restricted to the lobby"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"A couple discuss holiday plans", sp:["Partner A","Partner B"], intro:"a couple discussing their plans for an upcoming holiday", tr1:["So, what kind of holiday are you hoping for this time? Something busy and packed full of activities?","Honestly, no. After the year we have had, I just want something relaxing, no rushing around and no crowded itineraries, just time to unwind properly.","That suits me perfectly. Now, there are a few excursions on offer, there is a city tour, a mountain hike, or a boat trip out to a little island. Which appeals to you?","Oh, the boat trip out to the island, without a doubt. The city and the mountains can wait, I love the idea of sailing out to a quiet little island for the day.","Great choice. And should we sort out some transport to get around? They rent bikes and scooters at the resort, and cars too.","Let us rent a car, I think. A bike would be far too tiring in the heat and a scooter feels a bit risky to me, so a car is the sensible choice for exploring.","Agreed. So what are you most looking forward to about the whole trip?","The food, honestly. I could take or leave the shopping, and we can do the history another time, but Greek food is amazing and I cannot wait to try it all.","Me too. One thing, though, shall we try to avoid the crowds wherever we can?","Definitely. I do not really mind the heat, and the cost is manageable, but big crowds genuinely spoil a place for me, so let us steer well clear of the busy spots."], tr2:["Good plan. Now, when do you think is the best time to head down to the beach each day?","Early morning, before it gets too hot. By noon the sun is brutal, and the evening is lovely but too late for a proper swim, so first thing in the morning is ideal.","Sensible. And that island excursion, do you think we can just turn up on the day, or should we sort it out beforehand?","No, we really ought to book the island trip well in advance. It fills up fast in July, so leaving it until the day would be a real mistake, and reception said the popular slots go weeks ahead.","Right, I will book it online tonight, then. Now, what must we make sure not to forget to pack?","Sun cream, above all else. We will not need an umbrella or a coat in Greece in the summer, but without plenty of sun cream we will both burn to a crisp.","True. Is there anything you are actually worried about for the trip?","My one real worry is the heat in July. It is not the sea or the insects that bother me, it is coping with those very high temperatures.","We will keep to the shade. And before we come home, is there a souvenir you would like to take back?","Let us bring back some pottery. The jewellery is tempting and the local food would be nice, but a lovely piece of handmade pottery would last for years and remind us of the trip."], Q:[{"q":"The sort of break the couple are hoping to enjoy is one that is:","a":"B","o":["full of thrills","calm and restful","focused on heritage"]},{"q":"The day trip they settle on is a voyage out to:","a":"C","o":["an urban centre","the highlands","a small isle"]},{"q":"For getting around, they decide to hire a:","a":"A","o":["car","bicycle","moped"]},{"q":"What the traveller is keenest about on the trip is the:","a":"B","o":["past and heritage","local cuisine","browsing the shops"]},{"q":"The thing they are determined to steer clear of is:","a":"C","o":["the hot weather","the expense","large groups of people"]},{"q":"The point in the day they judge best for heading to the shore is the:","a":"A","o":["early hours","midday","late in the day"]},{"q":"With the boat outing, they agree they should reserve it:","a":"B","o":["on the very day","well ahead of time","over at reception"]},{"q":"The one item they must be sure to bring along is:","a":"C","o":["a rain shade","a warm jacket","sun lotion"]},{"q":"The single thing genuinely troubling the traveller is:","a":"A","o":["the high temperatures","the ocean","the bugs"]},{"q":"The keepsake they plan to carry home is a piece of:","a":"B","o":["jewellery","ceramics","local produce"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: the impacts of tourism", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below. Fill each gap with the precise word or words from the talk, staying within the word limit shown for every answer.", layout:"flow", flow:["BENEFITS OF TOURISM","It provides employment, in other words it creates {1}","down to","It draws in overseas {2} that strengthens the national economy","down to","HARMS OF TOURISM","It may harm the {3} through pollution and building work","down to","An excess of tourists is referred to as {4}","down to","It pushes up local {5} for housing and goods","down to","It may put local {6} at risk as traditions become staged shows","down to","POSSIBLE SOLUTIONS","Impose {7} on how many people may enter popular sites","down to","Encourage responsible {8} that respects locals and the environment","down to","Distribute visitors more evenly across the {9}","down to","Greatest gain comes when tourist spending stays {10}"], intro:"part of a lecture about the impacts of tourism on host communities", tr1:"Good afternoon, everyone. Today I want to explore the many impacts that tourism has on the communities that host it, both the good and the bad. Let us begin with the benefits. First and foremost, tourism creates jobs. Think of all the people employed in hotels, in restaurants and in transport, from taxi drivers to tour guides, all of whom depend on visitors for their livelihoods. So the very first great advantage is that tourism creates jobs. A second major benefit is economic in a different way, because tourism brings valuable foreign currency into a country. When overseas visitors spend their own money, that foreign currency helps the national economy and can be used to import goods the country needs. But it is not all positive. Tourism can also do real harm, and one of the most serious problems is that it can badly damage the environment, through pollution, litter and the endless construction of new hotels and roads. When a destination attracts far, far too many people, we end up with a phenomenon that experts now call overtourism. That word, overtourism, describes places that are simply overwhelmed by sheer numbers of visitors. And one direct consequence is economic pressure on the locals, because overtourism tends to raise local prices, the cost of housing, food and everyday goods all climbing steeply, making ordinary life much harder for the residents who live there.", tr2:"Beyond those rising prices, there is a subtler danger too. Mass tourism can threaten local culture, as age-old traditions are repackaged and turned into staged shows performed purely for the entertainment of tourists, losing much of their real meaning in the process. So the local culture itself is put at risk. Now, what can be done about all of this? Researchers and governments have proposed several solutions. One approach is to set firm limits on visitor numbers at the most popular sites, so that only a certain number of people are allowed in each day, and these limits protect fragile places from being loved to death. A second idea is to promote what we call responsible travel, encouraging tourists to behave in ways that respect local people, their customs and their environment. Responsible travel of this kind can make a genuine difference. A third strategy is to spread visitors more evenly across the different seasons of the year, rather than cramming everyone into the summer months, which eases the pressure on any single part of the calendar. And here is the key point to remember, communities benefit most of all when the tourist money stays local, when it goes into local pockets, local shops and local businesses, rather than leaking away to big foreign companies. Keep that word local firmly in mind, because that is where the real value truly lies.", Q:[{"q":"By offering work in hotels, restaurants and transport, tourism generates ______","a":"jobs","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"When visitors from abroad spend, they bring in valuable foreign ______","a":"currency|money","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Pollution, litter and constant construction mean it can damage the ______","a":"environment","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"A destination swamped by huge numbers of tourists is described using the term ______","a":"overtourism","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"A knock-on effect is a steep climb in the local ______ of housing and food","a":"prices","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"When customs are turned into performances for visitors, the local ______ is endangered","a":"culture","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"One remedy is to place firm ______ on daily visitor numbers at busy spots","a":"limits","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Another idea is to encourage a responsible style of ______","a":"travel","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"A further tactic is to spread arrivals more evenly through the ______ of the year","a":"seasons","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The biggest benefit occurs when the money from tourists remains ______","a":"local","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"Riverside Cookery School", blurb:"Course enrolment · Covered market map · Dinner party plan · Food & culture",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Cookery course enrolment", sp:["Officer","Caller"], instr:"Complete the enrolment table below. Write the answer that fits each gap, following the word limit shown for every item.", layout:"table", table:[["Detail","Response"],["Learner family name","{1}"],["Style of cooking chosen","{2}"],["Ability group","{3}"],["Total meetings in the course","{4}"],["Preferred day to attend","{5}"],["Starting time of the class","{6} pm"],["Full price of the course","£{7}"],["Item the learner must supply","{8}"],["How food materials are handled","{9}"],["Award received on finishing","given at the {10}"]], intro:"a telephone conversation between an enrolment officer at a cookery school and a man who wishes to join a course", tr1:["Good afternoon, Riverside Cookery School enrolment office, Diane speaking. How may I help you this afternoon?","Hello Diane. I picked up one of your colourful leaflets in the town library, and I would really love to enrol on one of your cookery courses, if there are still places left.","There are a few spaces left. Let me open a form for you. Could I start with your surname, your family name, first?","Yes, of course. My first name is Marco, and my surname is Bianchi. People nearly always get it wrong, so let me spell it out slowly. It is B-I-A-N-C-H-I, and that gives you Bianchi.","Thank you, so that is Bianchi, typed in exactly as you spelled it. Now, we teach French, Spanish, Thai and Japanese, among others. Which cuisine were you hoping to study?","For a while I was tempted by the Spanish tapas classes, but in the end I have set my heart on Italian cooking, the food my grandparents always made.","A lovely choice, Italian it is. And how would you describe your level? Our classes are grouped into beginner, intermediate and advanced.","I am well past the beginner stage, but I would never be bold enough to call myself advanced, so I think intermediate would suit me best.","Intermediate, noted. This course runs for six sessions in total, meeting once a week. On which day would you prefer to come along?","Weekday evenings are tricky for me because of work, so a weekend would be far easier. Could I come on Saturday, please? Saturday would fit nicely."], tr2:["Saturday is no problem at all, we have a very popular Saturday group. We run two separate sittings, one in the morning and one later on. Would you like the morning slot, or the afternoon one?","I am really not a morning person, so please do not put me down for the morning class. The afternoon suits me far better. Could I take the class that begins at two, two in the afternoon?","Two in the afternoon, that is booked. As for the fee, the course costs one hundred and fifteen, oh, I do beg your pardon, that is last year's price, it is actually one hundred and fifty pounds now. Please also bring your own apron, not a full set of chef's whites.","That is fine, one hundred and fifty pounds it is, and I will pack an apron of my own instead of the whites. Do I need to buy and bring in all the ingredients myself each week?","Not at all. All of the ingredients are provided for you here at the school, so you simply turn up and cook. And at the very end of the course, once you have completed all six sessions, you will receive a certificate.","Wonderful, a certificate at the end as well. Thank you so much, Diane, that is really helpful, and I feel much more organised now.","It has been my pleasure, Marco. We very much look forward to seeing you on Saturday. Goodbye for now."], Q:[{"q":"The learner spells out his family name for the office.","a":"Bianchi","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"He finally decides which national cuisine he wants to learn.","a":"Italian","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"He places himself in the middle skill band, not a novice and not expert.","a":"intermediate","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"He is told how many weekly classes make up the whole course.","a":"6|six","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"He asks to come at the weekend rather than on a working evening.","a":"Saturday","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"He books the later sitting that starts in the early afternoon.","a":"2|2pm|two","lim":"A TIME"},{"q":"He is quoted the corrected fee for the course.","a":"150|one hundred and fifty","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"He is asked to bring a single item of his own rather than a full uniform.","a":"apron","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"He learns that the food materials do not need to be bought by him.","a":"provided|included","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"He will collect his award once every session is complete.","a":"end","lim":"ONE WORD"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Covered market", map:STREET, intro:"a guide giving visitors a short talk about the layout of a covered market", tr1:"Welcome, everyone, to our wonderful covered market, and thank you all for joining this short tour. Before we set off, let me help you picture the layout, because it is really very simple once you have it fixed in your head. You come in through the main entrance, which sits at the bottom of the market, right in the middle. A wide corridor runs straight across the centre of the hall, separating the stalls along the top from the stalls along the bottom. Let us begin with the top row, furthest from the entrance. Tucked away in the very top left-hand corner you will find the bakery, with its wonderful smell of fresh bread. Moving along that top row towards the centre, just to the left of the middle, stands the butcher, always busy on a weekend. Then, crossing over the centre line and just to the right of the middle along the same top row, is the cheese stall, with dozens of varieties on display. Carry on to the far end and, in the very top right-hand corner, you reach the fishmonger, where the day's catch is laid out on ice. Now come back down towards where we are standing. In the bottom left-hand corner, over on this side near the wall, is the pretty flower stall, absolutely bursting with colour.", tr2:"Now let me point out the stalls down here along the bottom row, close to the entrance where we came in. Standing just to the left of the entrance, on this near side, is the coffee stand, and I do recommend a cup before you leave. Directly opposite, just to the right of the entrance, you will spot the fruit and vegetable stall, piled high with fresh produce from local farms. Keep going along the bottom row towards the far end, and in the very bottom right-hand corner you will come to the seating area, where you are welcome to sit down and eat whatever you have bought. A couple of practical points before I let you explore on your own. People sometimes assume we only open at weekends, and others think we shut on Saturdays and Sundays, but neither is true, in fact the market is open seven days a week, all year round. And when it comes to paying, you are not restricted in the slightest. Some markets insist on card only these days, and a few old-fashioned ones still want cash only, but here every single stall will happily take either cash or card, whichever you prefer. That is the end of the tour, so please do wander off and enjoy yourselves. Thank you very much.", Q:[{"q":"Where can the shop selling fresh bread be found on the plan?","a":"A"},{"q":"Which spot marks the stall dealing in fresh fish and seafood?","a":"D"},{"q":"At which point is the stall offering a range of cheeses located?","a":"C"},{"q":"Where is the stall run by the meat seller positioned?","a":"B"},{"q":"Which letter shows the stall full of cut flowers?","a":"E"},{"q":"Where should you head for a hot cup of coffee?","a":"F"},{"q":"At which spot is the stall piled with fresh produce and greens?","a":"G"},{"q":"Where is the area set aside for sitting down to eat?","a":"H"},{"q":"How often does the market open its doors?","a":"B","o":["only on working days","every day of the week","just at the weekend"]},{"q":"What forms of payment do the stalls take?","a":"C","o":["only bank cards","only notes and coins","either cash or a card"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Planning a dinner party", sp:["Host A","Host B"], intro:"two friends discussing the plans for a dinner party they are going to host", tr1:["Right, let us finally plan this dinner party. The first decision is what to cook. I did wonder about a French menu, and my sister keeps pushing an Indian feast with lots of spice.","Both are tempting, I admit, but I think we should keep it simple and do Italian. We both know Italian dishes really well, and everyone we have invited loves that food.","Italian it is then. So how many are we cooking for? I thought maybe a cosy four, or six at a push?","It has grown a bit, I am afraid. Once you count both of us and all the friends who said yes, it comes to eight altogether, so eight it is.","Eight, right, plenty of chairs then. For the starter, shall we do a fresh green salad, or some warm bread and olives?","A salad is boring for a special night, and bread alone is not really a starter. Let us begin with a simple soup, something warming we can make in advance.","A soup to start, lovely. And the main course? I could grill some fish, or do a proper steak if we feel extravagant.","Fish is tricky for eight at once, and steak is horribly expensive. Let us do pasta, definitely, it is the heart of an Italian meal.","Pasta for the main, agreed. Now for dessert, were you thinking a rich chocolate cake, or a light platter of fresh fruit?","Neither, really. There is only one choice for an Italian dinner, and that is tiramisu, everyone adores it, so let us finish with tiramisu."], tr2:["Now, where should we do the shopping? We could order everything online and have it delivered, or push a trolley round the big supermarket on the ring road.","Online is convenient, and the supermarket is cheap, but for a meal like this freshness matters most. Let us buy everything at the market, the produce there is much fresher.","The market it is, I love wandering round there anyway. We had better agree a budget, though. Shall we say around forty pounds, or stretch to a full hundred?","Forty would be far too tight for eight people, and a hundred feels a bit reckless. Let us set a sensible budget of around sixty pounds, that should cover everything.","Around sixty pounds, perfect. When should we do the cooking? We could leave it to the morning of the party, or get ahead and do it two days before.","The morning would leave us in a total panic, and two days ahead is too early for fresh food. Let us prepare most of it the day before, so on the night we can relax.","The day before, a wise plan. Oh, one important thing I nearly forgot, our friend Anna has a serious allergy, so we absolutely must avoid putting any nuts in anything.","Good point, thank you for remembering, no nuts anywhere on the menu. And finally, what shall we offer to drink? Some fizzy beer, or a big jug of fruit juice?","Beer does not really suit an Italian dinner, and juice on its own is a bit plain. Let us serve some nice wine with the meal, with a few soft drinks on the side for anyone who prefers."], Q:[{"q":"Which national style of food do they settle on?","a":"B","o":["food from France","food from Italy","food from India"]},{"q":"How many people will sit down to eat in total?","a":"C","o":["four diners","six diners","eight diners"]},{"q":"What will they serve as the opening dish?","a":"A","o":["a bowl of soup","a leafy salad","some bread"]},{"q":"What have they picked for the main dish?","a":"B","o":["grilled fish","a pasta dish","a steak"]},{"q":"How will the meal be rounded off?","a":"C","o":["a chocolate cake","a plate of fruit","a tiramisu"]},{"q":"Where have they decided to buy the food?","a":"A","o":["at the local market","at a large supermarket","over the internet"]},{"q":"Roughly how much do they plan to spend?","a":"B","o":["around forty pounds","around sixty pounds","around a hundred pounds"]},{"q":"When are they going to do most of the cooking?","a":"C","o":["on the party morning","a couple of days ahead","on the previous day"]},{"q":"Which ingredient must be kept off the menu entirely?","a":"A","o":["any nuts","any dairy","any eggs"]},{"q":"What will be the main thing to drink with the meal?","a":"B","o":["some beer","some wine","some fruit juice"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: food and culture", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below, which traces the talk on food and society. Write the answer for each gap, keeping to the word limit given for every item.", layout:"flow", flow:["A region's dishes grow out of its local {1}, and what the land can produce","In earlier times, spices were valued for keeping {2} from going off","As ships opened up the world, trade carried new {3} between continents","One example is the potato, which first came from South {4}","Eating together at one table builds a strong sense of {5}","In modern times, cheap fast food is tied to rising {6}","In response, the {7} food movement backs unhurried local eating","Meanwhile street food stays popular because it is quick and {8}","Family dishes are quietly handed down across the {9}","Ultimately, cooking is an expression of cultural {10}"], intro:"part of a lecture about the relationship between food and culture", tr1:"Good morning, everyone. Today I want to explore the deep and fascinating relationship between food and culture, because what a society chooses to eat tells us an enormous amount about who its people really are. Let us begin with the most basic influence of all. What a particular region eats very often reflects its local climate, and what can realistically be grown in that soil and weather. A hot, dry area will develop very different dishes from a cold, wet one. Moving back in time, we find that spices were once among the most highly valued goods on the entire planet. People sometimes assume this was purely for flavour, but that is only part of the story. In the days long before refrigeration existed, spices were prized above all because they were used to preserve meat and stop it spoiling. As sailing ships opened up the world, global trade began to reshape what everyone ate. That trade spread new crops right around the globe, moving plants between continents that had never known them. The potato is a perfect example. Although we think of it as thoroughly European today, the potato actually came originally from South America, before it went on to transform the diets of Europe entirely. And food is not only about survival. On a social level, sharing a meal around one table helps to build a genuine sense of community and belonging that few other activities can match.", tr2:"Let us now turn to the modern world, where our relationship with food has changed dramatically. Over recent decades, the rapid spread of cheap fast food has been closely linked to rising rates of obesity across many countries, a trend that worries doctors a great deal. Partly in reaction against this, a very different idea has taken hold. The so-called slow food movement actively promotes traditional, locally sourced meals that are cooked and eaten without hurry, as a direct answer to the fast food culture. Alongside all this, street food continues to thrive in cities everywhere. It remains hugely popular for a very simple reason, it is usually both cheap and quick, which suits busy people perfectly. Yet food is never only about the present moment. Think of how many of our most treasured recipes are quietly passed down through the generations, handed from grandparents to parents to children within a single family, often written on nothing more than a stained scrap of paper. When you cook one of those dishes, you are keeping a memory alive. So, to draw all of this together, we can see that food is far more than mere fuel for the body. In the end, cooking is a genuine expression of cultural identity, a way for a whole people to say who they are and where they have come from. Thank you all very much, and I look forward to taking your questions.", Q:[{"q":"A place's cooking mirrors the surrounding conditions of weather and land.","a":"climate","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Before fridges existed, spices chiefly stopped this food from spoiling.","a":"meat","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Sea trade moved these growing plants around the world.","a":"crops","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The potato originally belonged to this continent.","a":"America","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Sharing food helps to create this feeling of belonging.","a":"community","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Cheap fast food has been connected to this growing health problem.","a":"obesity","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"This movement pushes back by favouring slow, local meals.","a":"slow","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Besides being fast, street food appeals because it costs little.","a":"cheap","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Cherished recipes travel down through these successive family layers.","a":"generations","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"In the end, food lets a people declare their cultural sense of self.","a":"identity","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"Central Library", blurb:"Membership · Library floor plan · Research help · Future of libraries",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Library membership", sp:["Officer","Caller"], instr:"Complete the table below. Write the answer for each gap using the word limit shown in brackets.", layout:"table", table:[["Detail","Information"],["Family name","{1}"],["Type of card requested","{2}"],["Maximum items on loan together","{3}"],["Length of a book loan","{4} weeks"],["Daily charge for late returns","{5} pence"],["Included at no cost","use of the {6}"],["Way to extend a loan","{7}"],["Location of the silent reading zone","level {8}"],["Document needed to prove identity","a {9}"],["How often the events bulletin is sent","{10}"]], intro:"a telephone conversation between a library officer and a caller who wants to join the library", tr1:["Good morning, you are through to Central Library, how can I help you today?","Oh, hello there. I have just moved into the area and I would like to join the library, if that is possible. My surname is Kowalski, that is K-O-W-A-L-S-K-I.","Welcome to the neighbourhood. I can certainly set that up for you over the phone. First of all, would you like an adult card or a child card this morning?","It would just be for me, so an adult card, please, nothing for the children today.","That is absolutely fine. With a standard adult card you can borrow up to ten books at once, sorry, let me correct myself there, up to eight books at any one time.","Right, eight books, good to know. And how long am I allowed to keep them for once I have taken them out?","The loan period does vary a little. For DVDs it is two weeks, but for ordinary books you get a bit longer, that is three weeks in total before you need to bring them back.","That is generous. And what happens if I bring something back a little bit late by accident?","Please do not worry too much. If you are late, the fine used to be twenty pence, but these days we have lowered it, so it is only ten pence per day now."], tr2:["That all sounds very reasonable indeed, thank you for explaining it so clearly. Are there any other benefits or extras that come with being a member here?","Yes, there are several. As well as borrowing, your membership gives you free access to the computers, so you can come in and use them at no charge whenever you need to.","Excellent. And once I have borrowed my books, is it easy to renew them if I need a little more time?","It is very straightforward. You can renew your books online through our website from home, so there is no need to come in. And if you fancy somewhere peaceful to read, the quiet study zone is up on floor two.","Perfect. Is there anything I need to bring with me when I first come in to collect the card?","Just one thing for identification. Please bring a passport with you when you visit, as we need to see that before we can hand over your new card.","No problem at all, I will dig it out. Is there anything else I ought to know before I let you go?","Only that we like to keep our members well informed about everything going on. We send out an events newsletter to all our members, and that one goes out monthly, so you will always know exactly what talks and activities are coming up."], Q:[{"q":"Reader's family name","a":"Kowalski","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Category of card being set up","a":"adult","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"How many items may be borrowed at the same time","a":"8|eight","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Number of weeks an ordinary book may be kept","a":"3|three","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Amount charged for each late day","a":"10|ten","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Facility offered free with membership","a":"computers","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Method used to renew a loan from home","a":"online","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Floor where the peaceful study area sits","a":"2|two","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Item to bring in as identification","a":"passport","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Frequency of the members' newsletter","a":"monthly","lim":"ONE WORD"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Library floor plan", map:PLAN, intro:"a librarian describing the layout of the building using a floor plan", tr1:"Let me talk you through the library floor plan so that you know exactly where everything is before you start exploring on your own. The whole plan is laid out as a simple grid, with a row of rooms across the top and another row across the bottom, and a wide central corridor running between the two rows. You will be coming in through the main doors at the bottom centre of the plan, and that spot is marked clearly as the entrance. As you step inside, the very first thing you will see is the information desk, which sits just to the right of the entrance, so do stop there whenever you need a hand. Now, if we look right across to the top of the plan, the children's section has been given the whole of the top left-hand corner, where there is plenty of room for story time and picture books. Moving along that top row towards the middle, the fiction area is just to the left of centre, so that is where all the novels live. Directly across from it, just to the right of centre, you will find the non-fiction area, with all the factual titles neatly arranged. Finally, still along that very same top row, the reference section takes up the top right-hand corner, and do please remember that those particular books cannot be taken home with you.", tr2:"Now let us come back down to the lower half of the plan, along the bottom row. Over on the far left, the computer area occupies the bottom left-hand corner, so it sits diagonally below the children's section that we mentioned a moment ago. Coming back towards the middle along the bottom, the cafe is just to the left of the entrance, which makes it very easy to grab a coffee on your way in or out. And over on the other side, balancing it out, the bookable study rooms fill the bottom right-hand corner, which is nice and quiet and well away from the busy doors. Before I let you go and explore, I have two quick practical notes for you. First, people often assume that we shut at six in the evening, but in fact the library stays open a good deal later than that, closing at eight in the evening every single day of the week. And second, if you need to print anything at all while you are here, it is not free, I am afraid, and it is not five pence either, printing actually costs ten pence a page. So do keep a little change handy in your pocket for that, as the machines cannot take cards. Right, I think that covers everything you need to find your way around, so please do go ahead and explore.", Q:[{"q":"The point where you go to ask staff for assistance","a":"G"},{"q":"The area set aside for younger readers","a":"A"},{"q":"Where the novels are shelved","a":"B"},{"q":"Where factual and informational titles are kept","a":"C"},{"q":"The zone holding books that must stay in the building","a":"D"},{"q":"The spot with machines for public use","a":"E"},{"q":"Where visitors can buy a hot drink","a":"F"},{"q":"The rooms you can reserve for private work","a":"H"},{"q":"What time does the building shut in the evening?","a":"B","o":["six o'clock","eight o'clock","ten o'clock"]},{"q":"How much is charged to print each page?","a":"C","o":["it is free","five pence a sheet","ten pence a sheet"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Student asks the librarian for help", sp:["Student","Librarian"], intro:"a student asking a librarian for help with a research project", tr1:["Hello, I am working on a research project for my course and I was hoping you could point me in the right direction.","Of course, that is exactly what we are here for. Can you tell me what subject your project is on?","Well, to begin with I thought I might do it on biology, but in the end I settled on psychology, so it is psychology that I need material for.","A popular choice. For a subject like that, honestly the best resource is not just the books on the shelves, it is our online database, which has far more up-to-date articles.","That is useful to know. All the same, I would still like to browse a few physical books. Whereabouts are the psychology titles kept?","You will find them up on floor three. Not the first or the second floor, mind you, take the lift or the stairs all the way up to floor three.","Great. And once I have found some, how long am I allowed to borrow them for?","The same as everything else here, I am afraid, which is three weeks. Not a whole month, just the standard three weeks per loan.","That works. One more thing, if a book I want has already been taken out by somebody else, can I still get hold of it?","Yes, you can reserve it. The easiest way by far is to reserve it online rather than phoning us or coming in, and then we will email you the moment it comes back."], tr2:["Brilliant. Now, at some point I am going to need to make copies of a few pages. Where are the photocopiers?","The photocopiers are down on floor one. Not up on floor two or three where the books are, they are on the ground level, floor one.","Got it. And if I get completely stuck while I am searching, what should I do?","Do not struggle on your own. The best thing is to come straight to the desk, where a member of staff is always on hand to help you in person.","That is reassuring. My tutor also mentioned that I will need to reference everything properly. Do you have a guide for that?","We do indeed, and the good news is that it is completely free, so you do not need to pay anything or be a special member to take one.","Perfect. I may also want somewhere quiet to work. How long can I book one of the study rooms for?","You can book a room for up to two hours at a time, so not just a quick hour here and there, a good solid two hours to get your work done.","That should be plenty. And just so I am prepared, what happens if my books end up overdue?","There is no need to panic. Before any fine is ever added, you will always get an emailed reminder first, so keep an eye on your inbox rather than expecting a phone call or a letter."], Q:[{"q":"Which topic did the student finally decide to base the project on?","a":"B","o":["the past","the human mind","living organisms"]},{"q":"What does the librarian recommend as the strongest source of material?","a":"C","o":["the printed stock on the shelves","asking a member of staff","the electronic collection of articles"]},{"q":"On which level are the psychology books located?","a":"A","o":["the third","the ground level","the second"]},{"q":"For how long may the books be kept per loan?","a":"B","o":["seven days","twenty-one days","four weeks"]},{"q":"What is the recommended way to hold a book that is out on loan?","a":"A","o":["through the website","by calling in","by visiting the counter"]},{"q":"Where can the copying machines be found?","a":"C","o":["the third level","the second level","the ground level"]},{"q":"If the student is unable to make progress, what is advised?","a":"B","o":["searching the website","approaching the front counter","sending a message"]},{"q":"What is the cost of the citation handbook?","a":"A","o":["no charge at all","a two-pound fee","restricted to members"]},{"q":"What is the maximum length of a study-room reservation?","a":"C","o":["sixty minutes","the entire day","a couple of hours"]},{"q":"What will a borrower receive before any charge is applied to late books?","a":"B","o":["a telephone call","a message by email","a posted note"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: the future of libraries", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below. Write the answer for each gap using the word limit shown in brackets.", layout:"flow", flow:["Ancient world: the most celebrated early collection stood at {1}","Medieval period: hand-copied volumes were fastened to the {2} to prevent theft","Modern public library: paid for through {3}, giving free reading to all","Present day: visitors are given complimentary {4} access","Present day: many branches now loan practical objects like {5}","Present day: a variety of community {6} are put on for all ages","Reading habits: digital titles, known as {7}, have reshaped how we read","Main difficulty: most librarians point to {8} as their greatest problem","Social role: they offer people a welcoming, safe {9}","Core purpose: they stay essential hubs of {10} for the community"], intro:"part of a lecture about the history and future of libraries", tr1:"Good afternoon, everyone. Today I want to talk about the past, the present and the future of libraries, because they really do have a long and constantly evolving history that is well worth understanding. Let us begin right back in the ancient world. Of all the early collections that once existed, by far the most famous was the great library at Alexandria in Egypt, which was a vast store of knowledge and drew scholars from right across the known world to study there. Moving forward now to medieval times, books were produced entirely by hand, one page at a time, and were so precious and so valuable that, remarkable as it may sound to us today, they were literally chained to the shelves so that nobody could walk off with them. Then came a truly huge shift with the arrival of the modern public library. Because it was funded by taxes rather than by private wealth, it made reading available to absolutely everyone in the town, and, for the very first time in history, completely for free. And libraries have kept on changing ever since those days. Today they offer far more than just books alone. Most of them now provide free internet access for anyone who walks in through the door, and, rather interestingly, many now also lend out all sorts of practical items, such as tools and other pieces of equipment that you might only ever need to use once.", tr2:"So the modern library is really much more of a community hub than a simple book store. As well as lending things out, they host a whole range of community events, everything from story time for toddlers right through to job clubs for people who are looking for work. Of course, the way we read has been completely transformed by new technology. The rise of digital books, which we usually just call e-books, has changed our reading habits enormously, although I really should stress that print has certainly not disappeared and, in fact, remains hugely popular with many readers. Now, it is not all good news, I am afraid. If you were to ask librarians what the single biggest challenge they face is, most of them will not say technology at all, they will point straight to funding, because their budgets are so often cut by local councils. And yet, despite all of these money worries, libraries matter more today than they ever have. For a great many people they serve as a safe space, somewhere warm and welcoming that asks nothing of them at all. But above everything else, and this is the point I really want to leave you all with today, they remain absolutely vital centres of learning for the whole of the community. Thank you very much.", Q:[{"q":"Egyptian city famous for its great early library","a":"Alexandria","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What precious books were chained to in medieval times","a":"shelves","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Source of funding that made public libraries free","a":"taxes","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Type of free connection now provided to all who enter","a":"internet","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Example of the practical equipment now lent out","a":"tools","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Community activities regularly hosted by libraries","a":"events","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Common name for digital books","a":"ebooks|e-books","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The greatest challenge, caused by council budget cuts","a":"funding","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What a warm, welcoming library gives many people","a":"space","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What libraries remain vital centres of","a":"learning","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"Charity Run · Adventure Park · Research Methods · Bystander Effect", blurb:"🔴 HARD · self-correction distractors, faster speech", level:"hard",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Charity run registration", sp:["Officer","Caller"], instr:"Complete the table below. Write the answer for each numbered gap using the word limit shown after each question.", layout:"table", table:[["Detail","Information"],["Runner family name","{1}"],["Race distance selected","{2}"],["Day of this month she will run","{3}"],["Amount payable to enter (pounds)","{4}"],["Shirt size requested","{5}"],["Cause she is supporting","{6}"],["Time the race begins","{7}"],["Place where runners gather","{8}"],["Final digits of her phone number","{9}"],["Channel used to send news","{10}"]], intro:"a woman telephoning to register for a city charity run", tr1:["Good morning, City Charity Run registration line. My name's Rachel and I'll take your details today. How can I help?","Hello, yes, I'd like to sign up for this year's run, please. A friend did it last year and raved about it, so I thought I'd give it a go.","Wonderful, we'd love to have you. Let me open a new form. Could I take your surname, and would you spell it out so I get it right?","Of course. It's Whitfield — that's W-H-I-T-F-I-E-L-D, an F, not a V. People always try to put a V in there, but it's definitely an F.","Whitfield, spelt with an F, got it. Now, we run two distances. Which event would you like, the ten-kilometre or the half-marathon?","Hmm, I'll do the ten k... actually, no, make it the half-marathon. I've been training a fair bit lately, so I may as well push myself.","Good for you, the half-marathon it is. Next, the date you'll run. I originally wrote the thirteenth, but sorry, I misread; it's actually the twenty-third of this month. Does that suit you?","The twenty-third is fine by me, yes. That gives me a few weeks to build up my distance, so I'm happy with the twenty-third.","Perfect. Now the cost. The entry fee was thirty pounds, but I should mention it has just gone up, so it's now thirty-five. And would you like a T-shirt — shall I put you down for a medium?","Thirty-five, no problem. And yes to the shirt, though better make it a large, please, not a medium. I like a bit of room when I run."], tr2:["A large, noted. Now, this being a charity run, every entrant chooses a cause. Who would you like to raise money for this year?","I'd like all my sponsorship to go to the children's hospital, please. My little niece was treated there last winter, so it means a great deal to our family.","The children's hospital, a lovely choice, and very popular this year. Let me give you the timings. The run starts at a quarter past nine — no, hang on, let me check, it's a quarter to ten, so nine forty-five. And note the meeting point has moved, from the park to the pier.","Right, so nine forty-five, and we gather at the pier now instead of the park. The pier, got it. I'll note that so I don't turn up at the wrong spot.","Exactly, the pier, not the park. Last thing, I'll need a contact number so we can reach you if anything changes on the day.","Certainly. I won't read the whole thing out over the phone, but the important part is that my contact number ends in six-one-eight.","Ends in six-one-eight, got it. And so you know how we keep in touch, we send any updates through the app now rather than by email, so please download it.","Through the app, understood. I'll install it the moment we hang up. Thanks so much for your help — I'm really looking forward to the twenty-third."], Q:[{"q":"Runner family name","a":"Whitfield","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Race distance selected","a":"half-marathon|half marathon","lim":"NO MORE THAN TWO WORDS"},{"q":"Day of this month she will run","a":"23rd|twenty-third|23","lim":"A DATE"},{"q":"Amount payable to enter (pounds)","a":"35|thirty-five","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Shirt size requested","a":"large","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Cause she is supporting","a":"children's hospital|hospital|childrens hospital","lim":"NO MORE THAN TWO WORDS"},{"q":"Time the race begins","a":"9.45|9:45|quarter to ten","lim":"A TIME"},{"q":"Place where runners gather","a":"pier","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Final digits of her phone number","a":"618","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Channel used to send news","a":"app","lim":"ONE WORD"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Adventure park", map:PARK, intro:"a guide welcoming visitors to an adventure park and describing its layout", tr1:"Hello everyone, and a very warm welcome to the Adventure Park. Before you dash off to enjoy yourselves, do let me take a few minutes to talk you through the layout, because it's a big site and it's terribly easy to get lost on your first visit. Have a look at the plan on your handout as I go. Right now you're all standing together at the entrance, which sits at the bottom of the map, in the middle. Facing into the park from there, the very first thing you'll notice is the ticket office, the small building immediately to your right as you come in through the gate. If you haven't collected your wristbands yet, that's where you go. Now, directly opposite that, just to the left of the entrance as you look in, you'll find the toilets, so do make a mental note of exactly where those are. Let's turn our attention to the top of the site now, straight ahead across the far side. In the far left corner up there stands the zip-line tower, our tallest and most popular attraction of all. Right next to it, second along that top row, is the climbing wall, which is genuinely perfect for beginners and experts alike. Carry on in the very same direction and the third building along the top is the café, where you can grab a hot drink and a bite to eat whenever you fancy a break.", tr2:"Now for the top right. The very last space, in the far right corner at the top, is taken up by the picnic lawn, a lovely grassy area where you're welcome to sit and eat anything you've brought from home. Coming back down towards where we're all standing, in the near left corner, that is the bottom left of the site, you'll spot the first-aid hut, staffed all day by our trained team, so head straight there if anyone has a bump or a scrape. And finally, the whole of the near right corner, the bottom right, is taken up by the car park, so that's where those of you who drove will find your vehicles later on. A couple of important notes before I let you loose. Our closing time first: I very nearly said we shut at five, but let me correct myself, because in summer, which of course is now, the park stays open a whole hour longer and closes at six on the dot, so please do plan your day around a six o'clock finish. And one firm safety rule that we never bend for anyone: any child under the age of eight must be accompanied by an adult at all times, on every single attraction. They mustn't wander off on their own, not even for a moment. Right, that's everything from me, so go and have a fantastic time, and remember to keep that map handy.", Q:[{"q":"Where newcomers collect their wristbands","a":"G"},{"q":"The park's tallest and most popular ride","a":"A"},{"q":"A wall that suits beginners and experts alike","a":"B"},{"q":"Spot to buy a warm drink and a bite to eat","a":"C"},{"q":"The washrooms","a":"F"},{"q":"Where an injured visitor should head","a":"E"},{"q":"Grassy patch for eating food brought from home","a":"D"},{"q":"Where those who drove left their vehicles","a":"H"},{"q":"During summer, the time the park shuts is:","a":"B","o":["five o'clock","six o'clock","seven o'clock"]},{"q":"Youngsters below the age of eight are required to:","a":"C","o":["pay twice the price","put on a helmet","stay with a grown-up"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Planning a research project", sp:["Tutor","Student"], intro:"a tutor and a student discussing plans for a research project", tr1:["Come in, take a seat. I've read through your proposal, and today I want us to firm up the details of your project. Let's start with the big one: have you decided on your research method?","I have, more or less. I was originally thinking of interviews, they felt more personal... but a survey would reach far more people in the same time, so I've settled on a survey.","A survey, good, I think that's the right call. And how large a sample are you hoping for?","Well, I first planned a hundred, but a hundred felt a bit thin for the statistics, so I'll aim for two hundred to be on the safe side.","Two hundred is sensible, that'll give you more confidence in the results. Now, what's the main variable you're investigating?","I'm looking at how the amount of sleep students get affects their performance, so sleep is very much the key variable at the heart of it.","Sleep, lovely, a nice clear focus. And how are you going to collect the data from two hundred people?","I did consider paper forms, but that's slow and awkward to process, so I'll use an online questionnaire instead — it's much quicker and the answers come straight into a spreadsheet.","An online questionnaire, very efficient. Now let me push you a little. What's the single biggest risk to your results?","I've thought about that. It's not really the cost or the time, I think the biggest danger is bias, especially if only certain students bother to respond and skew the picture."], tr2:["Exactly, bias is the thing to watch. Now, before you collect any data, there's something crucial you must obtain first. What is it?","Oh, of course — I must get consent from every single participant before they take part. Nothing happens until I've secured their consent, I know that's non-negotiable.","Absolutely, consent comes first, always. And once the responses are in, which software will you use to analyse them?","I'll use SPSS. I did think about just using Excel, but we covered SPSS properly last term, so I'm comfortable with it and it handles this sort of statistics far better.","SPSS is a fine choice. One strong piece of advice: before the full survey, I'd really suggest you first run a small pilot to iron out any problems with your questions.","That's a good idea, actually. I'll run a small pilot on about ten people first, and if any questions confuse them, I can fix the wording before the real thing goes out.","Very wise. Now let's talk deadlines. When must all the data be collected by, do you reckon?","I'm aiming to have everything collected by week eight. That leaves me a decent stretch to write it up before the hand-in, so week eight is my target.","Week eight sounds realistic. And I'd like us to meet regularly to keep you on track — shall we say once a fortnight?","Fortnightly would suit me perfectly. Every two weeks feels about right, often enough to stay on course but not so often that there's nothing new to report."], Q:[{"q":"Which approach did she settle on for gathering data?","a":"B","o":["one-to-one interviews","a questionnaire survey","a controlled experiment"]},{"q":"How many respondents is she now aiming for?","a":"C","o":["fifty people","one hundred people","two hundred people"]},{"q":"What is the central factor she is examining?","a":"A","o":["amount of sleep","eating habits","stress levels"]},{"q":"The responses will be collected through:","a":"B","o":["printed forms","a web-based questionnaire","telephone calls"]},{"q":"What does she see as the greatest threat to her findings?","a":"C","o":["the expense","the time needed","skewed responses"]},{"q":"What must be obtained from each person beforehand?","a":"A","o":["their agreement to take part","financial backing","a booked room"]},{"q":"Which program will she rely on for the analysis?","a":"B","o":["Excel","SPSS","R"]},{"q":"What does the tutor advise doing first?","a":"A","o":["trial the survey on a few people","publish the outcomes early","take on paid helpers"]},{"q":"By when should all the data be gathered?","a":"C","o":["by the fourth week","by the sixth week","by the eighth week"]},{"q":"How often will the two of them meet?","a":"B","o":["once every week","once every two weeks","once every month"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: the bystander effect", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below. Write the answer for each numbered gap using the word limit shown after each question.", layout:"flow", flow:["When other people are {1}, an individual becomes less inclined to offer help","Each onlooker experiences a weaker sense of {2}","This mechanism is labelled {3} of responsibility","The phenomenon was studied intensively during the {4}","A single witness reacts sooner than someone standing in a {5}","Uncertain what is happening, people scan others for {6}","Wrongly concluding it is no emergency is termed pluralistic {7}","Being aware of the effect makes people readier to {8} in and act","Directing your plea at one {9} individual usually defeats the effect","The incident that first sparked the research occurred in {10}"], intro:"a lecturer giving a talk about the bystander effect in social psychology", tr1:"Good morning everyone. Today's lecture concerns one of the most striking and, frankly, unsettling findings in the whole of social psychology, something known as the bystander effect. Put simply, it describes the well-documented tendency for people to be less likely to help a victim in trouble when other people are present. Now, that may sound rather backwards; you'd imagine that the more help is on hand, the better a victim's chances. Yet the research shows precisely the opposite. The more witnesses there are to an emergency, the smaller each individual's personal sense of responsibility tends to become. Psychologists have a name for this mechanism: they call it diffusion of responsibility. Because the duty to act seems shared out among everyone in the group, each person quietly assumes that somebody else will surely step forward, and so, all too often, nobody does anything at all. This effect was first studied intensively by psychologists back in the nineteen-sixties, and it swiftly became one of the most researched topics of that era. In a whole series of carefully controlled experiments, investigators staged fake emergencies and watched closely how people reacted. The pattern was remarkably consistent. A lone bystander, someone who believed they were the only witness present, helped far more often, and far more quickly, than a person who found themselves in a large crowd of onlookers.", tr2:"So why on earth does this happen? A large part of the answer lies in how genuinely uncertain most emergencies really are. When we're unsure whether a situation is truly serious, we instinctively look to the other people around us for cues, watching their faces and their behaviour to work out how we ourselves ought to react. The trouble is that everybody else is doing exactly the same thing. If no one else appears alarmed, each person quietly concludes that the situation cannot really be an emergency after all, a collective misreading that researchers call pluralistic ignorance. Now, much of this modern research was originally sparked by a real and widely reported event. In that same decade, a young woman was attacked late at night in New York, and it was claimed at the time that many of her neighbours heard or saw something yet did nothing whatsoever. That disturbing case in New York, whatever its precise details, pushed the bystander effect firmly onto the scientific agenda. But let me end on a more hopeful note, because the findings are not all gloomy. Encouragingly, simply knowing that the bystander effect exists makes people noticeably more likely to step in when they witness trouble. And there's a simple practical trick: if you ever need help in a crowd, do not appeal to everyone in general. Instead, single out and directly ask one specific person, and that almost always overcomes the effect.", Q:[{"q":"When other people are ______, an individual helps less","a":"present","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Each onlooker feels a weaker sense of ______","a":"responsibility|responsible","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"This mechanism is labelled ______ of responsibility","a":"diffusion","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The phenomenon was studied intensively during the ______","a":"1960s","lim":"A DATE"},{"q":"A single witness reacts sooner than someone in a ______","a":"crowd","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Uncertain what is happening, people look to others for ______","a":"cues","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Wrongly deciding it is no emergency is termed pluralistic ______","a":"ignorance","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Being aware of the effect makes people readier to ______ in","a":"step","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Directing your plea at one ______ individual usually defeats it","a":"specific","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The incident that sparked the research happened in ______","a":"New York","lim":"NO MORE THAN TWO WORDS"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"Insurance Claim · Trade Fair · Dissertation Data · Expertise", blurb:"🔴 HARD · tricky spellings, numbers and corrections", level:"hard",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Home insurance claim", sp:["Agent","Caller"], instr:"Complete the table below. Write the answer for each gap using the word limit shown.", layout:"table", table:[["Detail","Information given"],["Reference on policy documents","{1}"],["Family name of caller","{2}"],["Object being claimed for","{3}"],["What caused the harm","a burst {4}"],["When it took place","{5} of March"],["Present worth of the object","£{6}"],["Amount subtracted from any payment","£{7}"],["Evidence the caller will send","a {8} of the receipt"],["Code to quote for this claim","{9}"],["Time before money is paid","about {10} days"]], intro:"a telephone conversation between an insurance agent and a caller making a home insurance claim", tr1:["Good morning, you have reached Shield Insurance, claims department. My name is Daniel and I will be helping you today. How can I assist you?","Hello, thanks. I need to make a claim on my home contents policy, please. Something at home got damaged and I would like to get the process started.","Of course, I can help with that. Before anything else, could I take your policy number, the one printed at the very top of your documents?","Yes, of course. It's P-G-four-four-two — that's P for Papa, G for Golf, not P-K as people sometimes hear it. So P-G-four-four-two.","Let me just read that back — P-G-four-four-two. Yes, that matches an account on our system. Thank you. And could I have your surname, spelled out for me?","It's Ashworth — I'll spell it for you: A-S-H-W-O-R-T-H, Ashworth.","Lovely, Ashworth, I've got that down. Now, which item exactly are you claiming for today?","My phone... no, sorry, ignore that, my laptop — the phone's completely fine. It's the laptop that was damaged.","Understood, a laptop. And what was it that actually caused the damage to it?","A burst pipe, if you can believe it. Water came right through and the whole desk was under water for hours.","So that's water damage from a burst pipe. And when did all this actually happen?","It was on the fifth of May... sorry, let me correct that, the fifth of March. Definitely the fifth of March."], tr2:["The fifth of March, noted here on the file. Now, what would you say is the current value of the laptop, roughly?","About eight hundred pounds — actually, thinking about it properly, eight hundred and fifty pounds. That's exactly what I paid for it when I bought it last year.","Eight hundred and fifty, thank you. I should mention there's a standard excess of one hundred pounds on this policy, which is simply deducted from any settlement we make. Do you happen to have a receipt for the purchase?","Yes, I kept it safely. I can send a photo of it over to you by email today, if that would help move things along.","A clear photo of the receipt would be perfect, thank you. Let me give you a claim reference now, so you can quote it whenever you contact us: it's two-seven-B.","Two-seven-B, got it, I've written that down carefully. And how long will it be until the claim is actually paid out?","Normally it takes fourteen days from start to finish, but for this particular type of water-damage claim it's usually ten days.","Ten days, that's great, much quicker than I had feared. Thank you so much for all your help this morning."], Q:[{"q":"The identifier printed at the top of the caller's paperwork.","a":"PG442|pg442","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The surname the caller spells out.","a":"Ashworth","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The single possession the caller decides to claim for.","a":"laptop","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What had split and let water through, ruining the item.","a":"pipe","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The exact day in March that the damage occurred.","a":"5th|fifth|5","lim":"A DATE"},{"q":"How much the item is reckoned to be worth now.","a":"850|eight hundred and fifty","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The fixed sum taken off before any settlement is paid.","a":"100|one hundred","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The kind of image of the receipt the caller offers to email.","a":"photo","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The short reference the agent gives for future contact.","a":"27B|27b","lim":"NO MORE THAN TWO WORDS"},{"q":"Roughly how many days this water-damage claim usually takes to settle.","a":"10|ten","lim":"A NUMBER"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Trade fair floor plan", map:PLAN, intro:"a guide describing the floor plan of a trade fair", tr1:"Welcome, everyone, and here's the floor plan of the trade fair, so let me walk you around it before you all set off. You come in at the bottom of the plan, through the entrance in the middle of the near wall. As you enter, the registration desk is right beside you on your right, so that's the very first thing you'll see, and do please check in there. Directly opposite the registration desk, on your left as you come in, you'll find the cloakroom, where you can leave your coats and bags. Now let your eye travel up to the top of the plan, along the far wall. The main stage fills the far left corner up there; that's where all the keynote talks happen. The next area along, second from the left on that top row, is the tech zone, which is packed with the latest gadgets and live demonstrations. Carry on rightwards and the food stalls come third along the top, so that's the place to head for lunch and coffee. Just to be clear, the cloakroom is not up on the top row at all — it stays down beside you at the entrance, on your left. So, to recap the top so far: main stage far left, tech zone second along, food stalls third. Do keep those in mind as we move on to the rest of the layout.", tr2:"Right, let's finish the tour with the remaining spaces. Back down at the bottom of the plan, the press room sits in the near left corner, so that's the corner nearest you on your left-hand side as you came in — journalists should head straight there. Now up to the top row again: the very last area, the far right corner along the top, is the VIP lounge, tucked away in the opposite corner from the main stage. And down at the bottom once more, the exhibition hall occupies the whole of the near right corner, a large space filling that corner nearest you on the right. So the exhibition hall and the press room face each other across the bottom of the plan. Two quick announcements before you go in. First, the opening hours: the fair is open until six this evening... sorry, let me correct that, it stays open until seven this evening, so you have plenty of time to see everything. Second, and this one is important, you cannot enter any area without a badge — not a printed ticket, and not photo identification, but your event badge, which you collect at registration. So please do wear your badge at all times. Enjoy the fair, everyone.", Q:[{"q":"Where visitors sign in the moment they arrive.","a":"G"},{"q":"The platform used for the keynote presentations.","a":"A"},{"q":"The area filled with new gadgets and live demos.","a":"B"},{"q":"The spot to head for lunch and a coffee.","a":"C"},{"q":"The place to hang up coats and leave bags.","a":"F"},{"q":"The room set aside for reporters and journalists.","a":"E"},{"q":"The exclusive area reserved for special guests.","a":"D"},{"q":"The large space given over to the exhibits.","a":"H"},{"q":"The time in the evening at which the fair closes.","a":"B","o":["until 6 pm","until 7 pm","until 8 pm"]},{"q":"What every visitor must wear to get into an area.","a":"C","o":["a printed ticket","photo identification","an event badge"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Two students discuss dissertation data", sp:["Maya","Tom"], intro:"two students, Maya and Tom, discussing the data for their dissertation", tr1:["Tom, we really need to sit down and decide what data we're using for the dissertation. Have you had any thoughts at all about where it should come from?","I did think seriously about running our own interviews at first, but honestly government statistics will be far more reliable and much easier to defend to the examiners, so let's use those rather than a survey.","Agreed, government statistics it is, then. And what time period do you think we should actually cover with them?","Let's cover twenty ten to twenty twenty, a full decade. That gives us a clean, recent ten-year window to analyse, and the figures for those years are complete.","Twenty ten to twenty twenty sounds absolutely ideal. And how many countries do you think we ought to include in the comparison?","Ten to start with... actually, no, let's include twelve, to be really thorough and to make the comparison a good deal stronger.","Twelve countries, good. Now, were the results roughly what you had expected when you first looked at them?","Honestly, no — the main finding was quite surprising, not at all what we had predicted, which actually makes it far more interesting to write about.","That is genuinely exciting. Were there any problems with the data itself that we ought to flag in the write-up?","Yes, unfortunately there are a lot of missing values for the early years, so we'll have to explain clearly how we handled those gaps."], tr2:["Right, we'll be sure to note the missing values in the methodology. So how should we actually present the findings to the reader?","A line graph will show the trend over the decade best, I reckon, much better than a pie chart or a bar chart would for this particular sort of data.","A line graph, agreed. Who's writing which section — shall we just split the work between the two of us?","Yes, you do the introduction, and I'll handle the analysis. That plays neatly to both our strengths, I think, and saves us treading on each other's toes.","Fine, I'll take the introduction, then. And what's the total word count we're aiming for again, remind me?","Eight thousand... no, sorry, ten thousand words in total. I really keep muddling that number up, don't I.","Ten thousand, noted. And what should our very next step be, this week, to keep us on track?","Let's draft the methodology section this week, while all of these decisions we've made are still fresh in our minds.","Good plan. And just remind me one more time, when exactly is the submission date?","It's the thirtieth — don't forget, the thirtieth of the month. We really cannot afford to miss it."], Q:[{"q":"Where the pair choose to obtain their figures from.","a":"B","o":["talking to people directly","official national records","a questionnaire they run"]},{"q":"The span of years their study will look at.","a":"C","o":["2000 to 2010","2005 to 2015","2010 to 2020"]},{"q":"How many nations they finally agree to compare.","a":"B","o":["ten","twelve","twenty"]},{"q":"How the central result struck them.","a":"A","o":["unexpected","just as predicted","hard to interpret"]},{"q":"The drawback they notice in the figures.","a":"C","o":["far too many entries","incorrect measurements","gaps with no values"]},{"q":"The way they decide to display the results.","a":"B","o":["a pie chart","a line graph","a bar chart"]},{"q":"Who takes responsibility for the opening section.","a":"A","o":["Maya","Tom","the two of them together"]},{"q":"The overall length they are aiming for.","a":"C","o":["six thousand words","eight thousand words","ten thousand words"]},{"q":"What they plan to tackle first this week.","a":"B","o":["gathering the figures","writing up the methods","preparing slides"]},{"q":"The day on which the work must be handed in.","a":"C","o":["the 13th","the 23rd","the 30th"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: expertise and deliberate practice", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below. Write the answer for each gap using the word limit shown.", layout:"flow", flow:["A well-known idea claims that {1} thousand hours of practice can make almost anyone world-class.","Research shows what really counts is not the amount but the {2} of the practice.","Psychologists point instead to what they call {3} practice.","This means concentrating fully right at the limit of your own {4}.","Ideally you also receive steady feedback from a {5}.","Merely redoing easy tasks makes many learners {6} and get stuck.","In certain sports, inborn {7} genuinely makes a difference.","Some physical traits, such as height and {8}, simply cannot be trained.","Real deliberate practice is demanding and hardly ever {9}.","So expertise grows from concentrated, {10} effort over many years."], intro:"part of a lecture about expertise and deliberate practice", tr1:"Today we're going to consider what it actually takes to become an expert in any field. There's a popular claim, one you've probably heard repeated many times, that ten thousand hours of practice will make almost anyone world-class at almost anything. It's a memorable figure, ten thousand hours, but the reality, as research suggests, is rather more subtle than that neat headline implies. What truly matters is not merely the quantity of practice, the sheer number of hours you put in, but its quality. That distinction is central to everything I want to say today. Specifically, what psychologists point to is something they call deliberate practice, and it is deliberate practice, not just any repetition, that really separates the best from the rest. So what does deliberate practice actually involve? It means working, with your full concentration, right at the very edge of your ability — pushing just beyond what feels comfortable, on tasks that have been chosen carefully to correct your specific weaknesses. And, ideally, it means doing all of this with regular feedback from a coach, someone who can watch you closely, spot your errors and tell you precisely how to improve. Without that steady feedback from a coach, progress tends to be far slower and much harder to sustain over time.", tr2:"Now, contrast that with what most people actually tend to do. Simply repeating what you can already do quite comfortably, however many hours it takes, produces very little improvement at all; in fact, a great many people plateau for exactly this reason, levelling off and then staying stuck at the same standard for years on end. That plateau is really the great enemy of expertise. The role of natural talent, meanwhile, remains hotly debated among researchers to this day. It clearly does matter in some fields — think of sport, for instance, where natural talent such as raw height or a particular physique simply cannot be trained into you, no matter how many hours you choose to practise. Motivation is crucial too, because deliberate practice is genuinely effortful and, let's be honest with ourselves, rarely enjoyable; it is not the pleasant, relaxing sort of activity that people so often imagine it to be. If it feels enjoyable and easy, you are probably not really doing it properly. So perhaps the single key lesson to take away today is this: expertise is built far less by talent alone than by years and years of focused, and frankly quite uncomfortable, effort. It is that sustained, uncomfortable effort, more than any natural gift, that ultimately turns a beginner into a true expert.", Q:[{"q":"The number of hours the famous saying refers to.","a":"ten|10","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The feature of practice that matters more than sheer hours.","a":"quality","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The specific label given to this effective form of practice.","a":"deliberate","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The personal boundary you should push right up against.","a":"ability","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The person whose guidance ideally accompanies your practice.","a":"coach","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What learners tend to do when they only repeat comfortable tasks.","a":"plateau","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The natural gift that plainly helps in some sports.","a":"talent","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The bodily build, alongside height, that cannot be coached.","a":"physique","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"How rarely this effortful practice feels pleasant.","a":"enjoyable","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The uneasy quality of the effort that builds expertise.","a":"uncomfortable","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"Lost Property · Community Centre · Field Trip · Colour Vision", blurb:"🔴 HARD · corrections and indirect map directions", level:"hard",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Lost property office", sp:["Officer","Caller"], instr:"Complete the table below. Write the answer for each gap using no more than the stated word limit.", layout:"table", table:[["Detail","Information given"],["Type of item mislaid","{1}"],["Colour of the item","{2}"],["Place where it went missing","On the {3}"],["Approximate time it was mislaid","{4}"],["Costly item packed inside","A {5}"],["Manufacturer of the case","{6}"],["Caller's family name","{7}"],["Tracking code assigned","{8}"],["Counter for collection","Desk {9}"],["Daily closing time","{10}"]], intro:"a caller reporting a lost item to a lost property office", tr1:["Good afternoon, this is the lost property office, how can I help you today?","Hello, yes, I'm afraid I've lost something on my journey home this afternoon. It was a bag... no, sorry, I should say a suitcase, a proper wheeled suitcase rather than a small bag.","Right, a suitcase, let me make a note of that down here. And what colour is the suitcase?","It's black — well, no, actually I always get this wrong; it's navy blue, definitely a dark navy blue, not black at all.","Navy blue, got it. Now, whereabouts exactly do you think you lost it?","At first I assumed I'd left it on the platform, but no, that isn't right — it was on the train itself, up in the luggage rack above the seats.","On the train, I see. And roughly what time would that have been?","It was around a quarter past four, I'd say... actually, let me think again, it was a little later than that, more like half past four, so 4.30 in the afternoon.","Half past four, thank you. And was there anything valuable inside the suitcase?","Yes, there was, and that's really why I'm calling in a bit of a panic — the main thing I'm worried about is a camera, quite an expensive one that I use for work."], tr2:["A camera, noted, we'll certainly keep an eye out for that when the bags come in. Now, can you tell me what make the suitcase is?","Yes, of course, it's a Samsonite — shall I spell that out for you so there's no confusion? It's S-A-M-S-O-N-I-T-E, Samsonite, one of the hard-shell ones with the ridged sides.","That's very helpful, thank you very much. And could I take your surname, please, for our records?","Certainly, my surname is Doherty — it's a tricky one, so I'd better spell that too, it's D-O-H-E-R-T-Y, Doherty.","Doherty, lovely, I've got that. I'll log the item under a reference number so that we can trace it quickly if it comes in. The reference will be L-two-nine, that is the letter L followed by the number two and then nine.","L-two-nine, right, I've written that reference down carefully in my diary.","Good, keep it safe. If the suitcase does turn up, you'll be able to come in and collect it in person during opening hours. When you do, please come to the counter marked desk three, not the main reception, but desk three specifically.","Desk three, thank you for being so clear about that. And until when are you actually open each day?","The office closes at half past five every weekday, so any time before 5.30 you'll find one of us here at the desk to help you.","Half past five, that's perfect, I'll try to pop in tomorrow. Thanks very much indeed for all your help with this."], Q:[{"q":"Type of item mislaid","a":"suitcase","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Colour of the item","a":"navy|navy blue","lim":"NO MORE THAN TWO WORDS"},{"q":"Place where it went missing","a":"train","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Approximate time it was mislaid","a":"4.30|4:30|half past four","lim":"A TIME"},{"q":"Costly item packed inside","a":"camera","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Manufacturer of the case","a":"Samsonite","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Caller's family name","a":"Doherty","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Tracking code assigned","a":"L29|L-29|l29","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Counter for collection","a":"3|three","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Daily closing time","a":"5.30|5:30|half past five","lim":"A TIME"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Community centre floor plan", map:PLAN, intro:"a member of staff describing the floor plan of a community centre", tr1:"Welcome, everyone, to our community centre, and thank you for coming along to the open day; let me talk you through the floor plan that you've each been given. You come in through the main entrance, which sits right in the middle of the bottom edge of the building, with a corridor running left to right across the centre and rooms arranged along the top and along the bottom. As you step through that entrance, the reception desk is the very first thing you meet, just to your right — so it is the room in the bottom row immediately to the right of the doors. Now look up to the top row, which stretches straight across the far side of the corridor. The main hall, our biggest space, fills the far left corner at the top. Right next to it, second along that top row as you move towards the right, is the gym, where we hold all our fitness classes. Carry on rightwards along the same top row and the third room along is the kitchen, which we use for our cookery evenings and coffee mornings. Now back down to the bottom of the plan: as you came in through the doors, the toilets were immediately to your left, that is the room in the bottom row just to the left of the entrance.", tr2:"Let me finish the tour of the plan and then give you two important notes. Still along the bottom row, past the toilets, the library corner tucks into the near left corner of the building — that is the bottom row, at the far left end, the corner nearest to you on your left as you come in. Then look back up to the top row for one final room: the meeting room takes the far right corner at the very top, sitting diagonally opposite the main hall. And finally, down in the bottom row once more, the storeroom sits in the near right corner, at the far right end of the bottom row. So the whole bottom row, reading from left to right, is library corner, toilets, entrance, reception, and then storeroom. Now, two things to remember before you book anything. First, the main hall cannot be reserved through our website and it cannot be booked by email either; the hall can only be booked by phone, so please ring the office directly to arrange it. Second, a quick word about parking: it is not the same for everyone. Parking here is free for members of the centre, but if you are not a member it will cost you two pounds for the day, so it is free for members and charged for everyone else.", Q:[{"q":"Where is the welcome desk that greets visitors located?","a":"G"},{"q":"Where can the largest assembly space be found?","a":"A"},{"q":"Where is the room used for exercise sessions?","a":"B"},{"q":"Where is the area used for cooking classes situated?","a":"C"},{"q":"Where are the washrooms positioned?","a":"F"},{"q":"Where is the little reading nook tucked away?","a":"E"},{"q":"Where is the space kept for gatherings and discussions?","a":"D"},{"q":"Where is the room used for keeping supplies?","a":"H"},{"q":"The only way to reserve the main hall is by:","a":"B","o":["sending an email","making a telephone call","using the online site"]},{"q":"The charge for leaving a car is:","a":"A","o":["waived for those who join the centre","never charged to anyone","charged to every visitor"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Two students plan a field trip", sp:["Student A","Student B"], intro:"two students discussing the arrangements for a college field trip", tr1:["So, remind me — where is the field trip actually going this year?","Well, I'd assumed we were heading to the forest like last time, but I checked the notice properly and it's actually the coast; we're going down to the seaside for the day.","Oh, the coast, that's nice. And how are we getting there — is it the train?","I thought it would be the train at first, and a couple of people were talking about going by car, but no — the department has booked a minibus for the whole group, so we all travel down together.","A minibus, good. And where are we supposed to meet in the morning?","That confused me too, to be honest. It's not the car park, as I first thought, and it isn't reception either; we meet at the main gate, right by the front entrance.","The main gate, got it. And what time do we need to be there?","They first said a quarter past seven, but let me check the email again... no, it was moved back; it's a quarter to eight now, so 7.45 sharp, don't be late.","Quarter to eight, noted. Is there anything in particular we need to bring with us?","Definitely bring waterproofs — not walking boots and not a tent, just a good set of waterproofs, because it is going to be wet and windy down there by the sea."], tr2:["What about the cost — how much is this trip going to set us back?","It was ten pounds when they first announced it, but they've actually raised the price since then; it's twelve pounds now, so make sure you bring twelve.","Twelve pounds, fine. Do we need to pack our own lunch as well?","No, that's the good news — we don't need to bring lunch and we don't have to buy it there this time; lunch is provided for everyone as part of the trip.","Lunch provided, even better. What are we actually going to be studying while we're there?","The focus this time isn't the birds and it isn't the plants; it's mainly the rock pools — we'll be examining all the little creatures living in the rock pools along the shore.","Rock pools, interesting. And when do we get back to college?","We should be back by six in the evening; not five, and hopefully not as late as seven, but six o'clock is the plan they've given us.","Six o'clock, right. Is there anything we really need to watch out for?","Yes — the main thing to be careful of isn't the weather and it isn't the traffic, it's the tides; the sea comes in very fast down there and we mustn't let ourselves get cut off."], Q:[{"q":"Which location is the group actually visiting?","a":"B","o":["the woodland","the seashore","the town centre"]},{"q":"How will everyone travel to the site?","a":"C","o":["by rail","by private car","by shared van"]},{"q":"Where has the group been told to gather beforehand?","a":"B","o":["by the parking area","at the front entrance gate","at the reception area"]},{"q":"What is the revised time they must arrive?","a":"C","o":["a quarter past seven","half past seven","a quarter to eight"]},{"q":"What item are they instructed to take along?","a":"B","o":["sturdy footwear","rain gear","camping shelter"]},{"q":"What is the updated price of the outing?","a":"B","o":["ten pounds","twelve pounds","fifteen pounds"]},{"q":"What is the arrangement for the midday meal?","a":"B","o":["something they must pack themselves","supplied for them","purchased on arrival"]},{"q":"What will they mainly be looking at?","a":"B","o":["seabirds","tidal pools","coastal plants"]},{"q":"By what time are they expected back at college?","a":"B","o":["five in the evening","six in the evening","seven in the evening"]},{"q":"What is the chief danger they are warned about?","a":"B","o":["the changing weather","the incoming sea","the passing traffic"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: how we see colour", instr:"Complete the flow-chart below. Write the answer for each gap using no more than the stated word limit.", layout:"flow", flow:["Colour does not belong to objects themselves; it is actually produced by the {1}","Incoming light strikes a thin layer at the rear of the eye known as the {2}, where light-sensitive cells sit","One kind of cell, the {3}, functions in low light yet registers no colour","The other kind, the {4}, picks up colour but only when the light is bright","Typically a person is equipped with {5} varieties of colour-detecting cell","These cells respond to red, to green and to {6} light","A common effect of colour-blindness is mixing up red with {7}","Certain birds are even able to see {8} light beyond our range","In humans, the disorder normally stems from a defect in a single kind of {9}","Our sense of a steady colour world exists because the brain adjusts for shifting {10}"], intro:"a lecturer explaining how the human eye and brain perceive colour", tr1:"Good morning. Today we are going to consider one of the most surprising facts in the whole of human biology: how it is that we manage to see colour. The first thing to grasp is that colour is not really a property of the objects out there in the world at all. Strange as it may sound, colour is created by the brain; it is a kind of interpretation, a story that the mind tells itself about the light reaching us. So where does that process actually begin? Light of many different wavelengths enters the eye, and at the very back of the eye it lands on a thin layer called the retina. It is here, on the retina, that the real work starts, because this surface is lined with special light-sensitive cells. Now, there are two main kinds of these cells, and it is well worth learning the difference between them. The first kind are called rods. Rods are extremely sensitive and they work well in dim light, at night or in a darkened room, but here is the catch: rods see no colour at all, only shades of grey. The second kind are the cones. Cones are almost the opposite; they detect colour beautifully, but they need bright light to do their job, which is why colours seem to fade in the dark. Most humans, it turns out, have three distinct types of cone inside the eye.", tr2:"So we have three types of cone, and each type is tuned to a different part of the spectrum. One type responds most strongly to red light, a second responds most strongly to green light, and the third responds to blue light; and from the mixture of the signals coming from these red, green and blue cones, the brain constructs every single shade that we are able to perceive. This also neatly explains colour-blindness. People who are colour-blind usually have some fault in one type of cone, and the most common result is that they find it hard to tell certain colours apart; most often they confuse red and green, which can make reading traffic lights genuinely tricky. It is worth adding that many animals do far better than we do. Birds, for example, possess a fourth type of cone that we simply lack, and this allows them to perceive ultraviolet light, a part of the spectrum that is completely invisible to human eyes. So remember: the human weakness in colour-blindness is essentially a fault in one type of cone, whereas the bird's extra cone is a genuine advantage. And the final, remarkable point is this: our impression of living in a stable, unchanging world of colour is very largely an achievement of the brain, which quietly corrects for the constantly changing light around us.", Q:[{"q":"Colour does not belong to objects themselves; it is actually produced by the ______","a":"brain","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Incoming light strikes a thin layer at the rear of the eye known as the ______, where light-sensitive cells sit","a":"retina","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"One kind of cell, the ______, functions in low light yet registers no colour","a":"rods","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The other kind, the ______, picks up colour but only when the light is bright","a":"cones","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Typically a person is equipped with ______ varieties of colour-detecting cell","a":"three|3","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"These cells respond to red, to green and to ______ light","a":"blue","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"A common effect of colour-blindness is mixing up red with ______","a":"green","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Certain birds are even able to see ______ light beyond our range","a":"ultraviolet","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"In humans, the disorder normally stems from a defect in a single kind of ______","a":"cone","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Our sense of a steady colour world exists because the brain adjusts for shifting ______","a":"light","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"Theatre Booking · Museum Wing · App Project · Timekeeping", blurb:"🔴 HARD · dense corrections, mixed question focus", level:"hard",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Theatre box office", sp:["Officer","Caller"], instr:"Complete the theatre booking record below. Write ONE WORD AND/OR A NUMBER for each answer unless a different limit is shown.", layout:"table", table:[["Booking detail","Information given"],["Production chosen","{1}"],["Evening selected","{2}"],["Quantity of seats","{3}"],["Part of the auditorium","{4}"],["Cost per seat","£{5}"],["Family name for the booking","{6}"],["Reduced-rate category claimed","{7}"],["Method of paying","{8}"],["Where to pick up the tickets","the {9}"],["Time the performance begins","{10}"]], intro:"You will hear a phone call between a theatre box office officer and a caller who wants to book some tickets", tr1:["Good afternoon, you've reached the Grand Theatre box office, this is the ticketing team, how can I help you today?","Hello, yes, I'd like to book some tickets, please. I've been meaning to come for ages. It's for the big Shakespeare production you've got on this month.","Wonderful, we've got several running at the moment. Which play were you hoping to see, was it Macbeth?","I nearly said Macbeth, actually, but no, sorry, I mean Hamlet. It's Hamlet we want, my friends have all raved about your production of Hamlet.","Excellent choice, Hamlet it is. And which night would suit you, we still have some good availability right across the week?","Let me think for a second. I was going to say Friday, but actually, no, make it Saturday, because more people can come along on the Saturday.","Saturday, lovely. And how many tickets shall I put you down for altogether?","Two to begin with, but, no, make it three, my friend's just decided she's coming too, so three tickets in total, please.","Three it is, then. Now, would you prefer seats down in the stalls, near the front, or up in the circle?","Oh, the circle, please. I always think you get a much better view of the whole stage from up in the circle.","Good choice. The circle seats are normally twenty-five pounds each, though I should mention, sorry, for a Saturday performance it's twenty-eight pounds each.","Twenty-eight pounds each, that's absolutely fine. We really don't mind paying a bit more for the Saturday."], tr2:["Lovely, let me take a few details from you then. Could I take the surname the whole booking should go under, please?","Yes, of course. It's Beaumont. It's one that people very often spell wrong, so let me give it to you letter by letter, that's B-E-A-U-M-O-N-T, Beaumont.","Thank you, Beaumont, I've got that written down. Now, will any concessions apply to your group, does anyone qualify for a reduced rate?","I did wonder about a senior rate for my uncle, but no, in the end it's just the three of us, and we're all students at the university, so the student concession, please.","Right, three student tickets noted there. And how would you like to pay for those today, we can take cash on the door or a card over the phone?","I'll pay by card, if that's alright. I nearly said I'd bring cash on the night, but no, let's do it now by card just to be safe.","Card's perfect, I'll take those numbers in a moment. Once that's done, you can collect the tickets on the night at the box office, just come to the box office window when you arrive. And do note that the show starts at half past seven.","Half past seven, and I collect them at the box office, got it. Thank you so much for all your help."], Q:[{"q":"Which Shakespeare drama did the caller finally decide on?","a":"Hamlet","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"On which day of the week will they attend?","a":"Saturday","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"How many seats were eventually reserved?","a":"3|three","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"In which section of the theatre did they choose to sit?","a":"circle","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What amount is charged for a single seat on that night?","a":"28|twenty-eight","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"Under what surname is the reservation being held?","a":"Beaumont","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What kind of discount does the group qualify for?","a":"student","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"How does the caller settle the bill?","a":"card","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"From which location will the group obtain their tickets on the evening?","a":"box office","lim":"NO MORE THAN TWO WORDS"},{"q":"At what time is the curtain due to rise?","a":"7.30|7:30|half past seven","lim":"A TIME"}]},
  {n:2, title:"New museum wing", map:PLAN, intro:"You will hear a museum guide describing the layout of a brand new wing to a group of visitors", tr1:"Welcome, everyone, and let me guide you around our brand new wing before you go off and explore it on your own. You'll come in through the main entrance, which sits right in the middle of the near wall, at the bottom of the plan as you're looking at it. As you step inside, the ticket desk is immediately to your right, just to the right of that entrance, so do stop there first to pick up your audio guides. Now let me take you along the top wall, the far side of the wing. Right in the far left corner, at the very top on the left, you'll find our magnificent Egyptian gallery, the real pride of the whole collection. Directly next to it, second along the top wall, is the Roman gallery, so the Egyptian and Roman rooms sit side by side up there. Carry on and third along the top you'll come to the café, a lovely spot for a rest and some tea. Then coming back down to the near wall, where you first entered, look just to the left of the entrance, and there you'll see the cloakroom, where you can leave your coats and bags before you wander round. So remember, ticket desk on the right of the entrance, cloakroom on the left of it, and the galleries running along the top.", tr2:"Let me now point out the last few spaces, and mention a couple of important rules. Back on the near wall, in the near left corner, that's the bottom left as you look at the plan, you'll find the gift shop, tucked neatly into that left-hand corner. Then, up on the top wall again, over in the far right corner, right at the very top on the right, is our special exhibition space, which changes every few months. And finally, in the near right corner, the bottom right of the plan, the lecture theatre takes up that whole corner, sitting opposite the gift shop across the wing. Now, a quick word on photography. I know some venues ban it altogether, and others happily let you use flash, but here photography is allowed as long as you switch your flash off, so pictures are fine, just no flash please. And one more thing about tickets. A lot of people assume the wing is free on weekdays, or perhaps on Saturdays, but in fact entry to the wing is free only on Sundays, and not on any other day of the week. Do enjoy your visit, and don't hesitate to ask any of our staff if you happen to get lost.", Q:[{"q":"Where can visitors collect an audio guide when they first arrive?","a":"G"},{"q":"Which room houses the collection the museum is proudest of, from ancient Egypt?","a":"A"},{"q":"Where is the display devoted to ancient Rome situated?","a":"B"},{"q":"Where might guests pause for a hot drink and a rest?","a":"C"},{"q":"Where should coats and bags be left before touring the wing?","a":"F"},{"q":"Where is the shop selling souvenirs located?","a":"E"},{"q":"Where is the space set aside for temporary, rotating displays?","a":"D"},{"q":"Where are talks and presentations held?","a":"H"},{"q":"The rule on taking pictures is that photography is:","a":"B","o":["not permitted at all","permitted provided the flash is off","permitted including the use of flash"]},{"q":"There is no charge to enter the wing on:","a":"C","o":["Monday to Friday","Saturdays","Sundays"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Group project: designing an app", sp:["Student A","Student B"], intro:"You will hear two students discussing a group project to design a mobile app", tr1:["Right, we really need to nail down what our app's actually going to do. Any ideas to get us started?","Well, my very first thought was a budgeting app, something to track your spending, but honestly there are loads of those already. Let's make a fitness app instead, something to keep people active. A fitness tracker, definitely.","Good call, fitness it is. So who's our target user, who are we actually building this for?","I was picturing busy adults at first, people with office jobs, but really we should design it for students like us. We understand students best, so let's aim it squarely at students.","Makes sense. And which platform should we launch on first, since we can't do everything at once?","I was leaning towards iOS because it looks so slick, but thinking about it, Android is far more common among students here, so let's build for Android first and add the others later.","Fair enough. What about the colour scheme, what sort of look are we going for?","I tried a blue palette to begin with, but it felt too corporate, a bit cold and business-like. Let's go with green instead, it feels healthy and fresh, perfect for a fitness app. Green all the way.","Love it. And the main feature, the one thing the app absolutely has to have?","There's chat and maps we could add later, but the core has to be workout reminders, little notifications that nudge you to get up and exercise. Reminders are the real heart of it, definitely."], tr2:["Great stuff. So how many testers should we recruit before we actually launch?","Let's see, I first said ten to keep it manageable, but honestly ten feels too few to spot the problems. Let's aim for twenty testers, that'll give us far better feedback. Twenty it is.","Twenty, noted. And when's the whole thing actually due, what's our deadline?","It's not week six, thankfully, and it's not week eight either, though people keep muddling those two up. The real deadline is week ten, so we've got a little more breathing room than some groups.","Phew, week ten. Now, who's going to design the logo for us?","Well, the tutor certainly won't do it for us, and I really don't want to leave it as nobody's job. Priya's brilliant at graphics, so let's ask Priya to design the logo, she'll do a lovely one.","Perfect, Priya on the logo. And when shall we all meet up to work on this?","Tuesdays are hopeless for half the group, and Fridays clash with the lab session, but Thursdays work for absolutely everyone, so let's make Thursdays our regular meeting day.","Thursdays it is. And for the final presentation, how should we show off the app?","We could just do slides, or bring along a poster, but that's a bit flat, isn't it? We should show a live demo of the app actually running, that'll really impress them. A live demo, definitely."], Q:[{"q":"What sort of application did the group finally agree to build?","a":"B","o":["managing money","staying fit","preparing meals"]},{"q":"Who is the app mainly intended for?","a":"C","o":["young children","working professionals","people studying at university"]},{"q":"Which system will they release the app on to begin with?","a":"B","o":["Apple devices","Android devices","a browser version"]},{"q":"What colour did they settle on for the design?","a":"B","o":["a blue look","a green look","a red look"]},{"q":"What did they decide the central function must be?","a":"B","o":["messaging","exercise prompts","location maps"]},{"q":"How many people will they bring in to trial the app?","a":"B","o":["ten","twenty","fifty"]},{"q":"When must the finished project be handed in?","a":"C","o":["in week six","in week eight","in week ten"]},{"q":"Who has been asked to create the logo?","a":"A","o":["Priya","their tutor","no one so far"]},{"q":"Which day did the group pick for their regular get-togethers?","a":"B","o":["Tuesdays","Thursdays","Fridays"]},{"q":"How do they plan to showcase the app at the end?","a":"B","o":["just some slides","a working demonstration","a printed poster"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: the history of timekeeping", instr:"Complete the flow-chart showing the development of timekeeping. Write ONE WORD for each answer unless a different limit is shown.", layout:"flow", flow:["The oldest known instrument was the {1}, which reads the hour from a shadow.","However, it could not work at {2}, when there is no sunlight.","In the dark, people instead relied on water {3} that tracked dripping water.","In medieval Europe, the mechanical clock was powered by falling {4}.","In the 17th century the swinging {5} sharply improved accuracy.","Reliable clocks let sailors calculate their {6} out at sea.","The spring-driven {7} made an accurate timepiece truly portable.","Today the most precise instruments are {8} clocks.","These work by counting the vibrations of {9}.","Modern satellite {10} depends entirely on them."], intro:"You will hear a lecture on the history of timekeeping", tr1:"Good morning. Today's lecture traces the long story of how humanity has learned to measure time, from shadows on the ground to the ticking of atoms. The very earliest device we know of was the sundial, a simple instrument that tells you the hour from the length and direction of the shadow that the sun casts across a marked surface. Clever though it was, the sundial had one very obvious weakness: it was completely useless at night, when of course there is no sunlight at all, and it was equally useless under heavy cloud. So how did ancient peoples tell the time in the dark? Their answer was the water clock. These water clocks worked by tracking the slow, steady dripping of water from one vessel down into another, and by marking the rising level they could measure the passing hours whether or not the sun was shining. A great leap forward then came in medieval Europe with the invention of the mechanical clock. Rather than sun or water, this new machine was driven by falling weights, heavy weights slowly pulling on a rope to turn the gears, although, it has to be said, those early mechanical clocks were wildly inaccurate. The real breakthrough in accuracy arrived in the seventeenth century with the pendulum. This swinging pendulum reduced a clock's error dramatically, from many minutes a day down to just a few seconds.", tr2:"Why did such accuracy matter so much? One important answer lay far out on the ocean. Accurate, portable clocks were of enormous value to sailors, because a reliable clock was exactly what they needed in order to work out their longitude, that is, their east-west position, while they were far out at sea. Without knowing the precise time on land, a ship simply could not fix how far east or west it had travelled. The next step made timekeeping truly personal. The invention of the spring-driven watch, powered by a tightly coiled spring rather than a hanging weight, meant that an accurate timepiece could at last be carried in a pocket or worn on the wrist. Suddenly the individual, and not just the town clock, could carry the time around. And today? The most accurate timekeepers ever built are atomic clocks. Rather than shadows, water or springs, these atomic clocks measure the incredibly rapid and incredibly regular vibrations of atoms, and they are so precise that they lose barely a second over many millions of years. We depend on them far more than we realise, because modern systems such as satellite navigation, the very technology that guides your phone and your car, rely completely on the steady timekeeping of atomic clocks. So from the sundial to the atom, our quest to measure time has utterly transformed the world.", Q:[{"q":"Name the earliest timekeeping instrument.","a":"sundial","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"State the time of day when a sundial fails to function.","a":"night","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What type of water device let people measure time after dark?","a":"clocks","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What falling objects turned the gears of medieval mechanical clocks?","a":"weights","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Which swinging component brought a major gain in accuracy?","a":"pendulum","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What east-west position could sailors then determine?","a":"longitude","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Which spring-powered device could be carried in a pocket?","a":"watch","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"What kind of clocks are the most accurate ever made?","a":"atomic","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The rapid regular vibrations of what are counted by these clocks?","a":"atoms","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Which navigation technology relies completely on atomic clocks?","a":"navigation","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]},
 {name:"Removals Quote · Business Park · Dissertation Plan · Habits", blurb:"🔴 HARD · numbers, corrections, indirect directions", level:"hard",
  parts:[
  {n:1, title:"Removals company quote", sp:["Officer","Caller"], instr:"Complete the removals quote record below. Write the exact word, number, date or name you hear in each gap, keeping within the stated limit for each entry.", layout:"table", table:[["Detail","Customer's answer"],["Type of property being vacated","a {1}"],["Bedrooms in the property","{2}"],["Chosen day for the move","{3}"],["City they are relocating to","{4}"],["Level the current property sits on","{5} floor"],["Delicate belongings needing care","{6}"],["Approximate box count","{7}"],["Final price of the job","£{8}"],["Sum paid up front to secure the slot","£{9}"],["Family name for the booking","{10}"]], intro:"a phone call between a removals company officer and a customer asking for a quote to move house", tr1:["Good morning, City Movers, this is the booking office, how can I help you today?","Oh hello, yes, I'd like to get a quote for a house move, please. Well, when I say house, it's actually a flat, so let me be accurate, it's a flat we're leaving, not a house.","No problem at all, I'll write it down as a flat. And how many bedrooms does the flat have?","Let me think for a second. Three... no, sorry, that's not right, it's two. Definitely two bedrooms, I don't know why I said three.","Two bedrooms, lovely. And what date were you hoping to move on?","The eighth of next month, oh, hang on, no, I've muddled that up, it's the eighteenth. The eighteenth is the day we actually get the keys handed over.","The eighteenth, got it, thank you. And whereabouts are you moving to?","We're heading down to Bath, actually, I keep saying that by mistake, it's Bristol, not Bath. Bristol is where the new place is.","Right, Bristol, I've corrected it here. And which floor is your current flat on?","It's on the ground floor... no, listen to me, that's our very first flat I'm thinking of. This one is up on the third floor, and I really should warn you that there's no lift at all in the building, so it's all going to be up and down the stairs."], tr2:["Thanks very much for the warning about the stairs, that's really useful for us to know. Now, do you have any fragile items that we should take extra care with?","Yes, quite a few, actually. The main thing to be careful of is several mirrors, big ones, so those will need proper padding and wrapping before they go on the van.","We'll wrap the mirrors very carefully, don't worry about those. Roughly how many boxes do you think you'll have altogether?","I reckon about twenty-five... no, thinking about all the kitchen things as well, it's closer to thirty. Let's say thirty boxes to be on the safe side.","Thirty boxes, noted. Right, let me add all of that up for you. For a two-bedroom flat going down to Bristol, the basic figure comes to four hundred pounds, but because of the third floor with no lift, the stairs push it up to four hundred and fifty.","Four hundred and fifty, all right, that's within what I was expecting to pay, so that's absolutely fine by me.","Great. To hold the booking for you we take a small deposit of fifty pounds, and then the rest of the money is due on the day of the move itself.","Fifty pounds deposit, no problem at all, I'm happy to pay that now over the phone if you like.","Perfect, thank you. Could I just take your surname for the booking, please?","Yes, of course, it's Kavanagh, and I'll spell that for you, K-A-V-A-N-A-G-H, Kavanagh."], Q:[{"q":"The kind of home the caller is leaving is a...","a":"flat","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"How many bedrooms the property contains.","a":"2|two","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The day of the month they will actually shift their belongings.","a":"18th|eighteenth|18","lim":"A DATE"},{"q":"The place they are moving their household to.","a":"Bristol","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Which storey the flat they are leaving is located on.","a":"third|3","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The breakable objects the movers should handle with special care.","a":"mirrors","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Roughly how many cartons will need shifting in total.","a":"30|thirty","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The complete cost the company quotes for the removal.","a":"450|four hundred and fifty","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The advance payment required to reserve the date.","a":"50|fifty","lim":"A NUMBER"},{"q":"The customer's surname as given for the reservation.","a":"Kavanagh","lim":"NO MORE THAN TWO WORDS"}]},
  {n:2, title:"Business park map", map:STREET, intro:"a manager describing the layout of a business park to a group of new visitors", tr1:"Right everyone, let me talk you through the layout of the business park before your visit, because it really is easy to get lost on your first day. As you arrive, you come in through the entrance at the bottom of the site, in the middle of the lower row, and there's a corridor, or roadway if you like, running straight across between the two rows of buildings. The first thing to find is reception. Reception is the unit immediately on your right as you walk in through the entrance, so it sits in the lower row just to the right of the gate. Now look at the top row, the row that is furthest away from the entrance. Building one, which holds the main offices, is right over in the far left corner at the top of the site. Moving along that same top row towards the right, the warehouse is the second unit along, sitting next to the offices. Carry on rightwards and the canteen is the third unit along the top, so it's between the warehouse and the far corner. Then come back down to the bottom for a moment: as you walk in and turn to your left, the car park is the unit just to your left, the one directly beside the entrance on the left-hand side. Do keep all of that geography in your head, because visitors and deliveries use different parts of the site and I don't want anyone wandering into the wrong building.", tr2:"Let me finish the tour of the lower row and then I'll add a couple of important notes. Still at the bottom, the loading bay is tucked right into the near left corner of the site, so it is the far left unit of the lower row, out beyond the car park. Over on the top row again, the data centre occupies the very far right corner at the top, sitting diagonally opposite the main offices. And back at the bottom, on the other side from the loading bay, the security lodge is in the near right corner, the far right unit of the lower row, so the guards can watch everyone coming and going. Now, two things you really must remember. First, the timing of the main gates. They are not open all night; the main gates close at eight in the evening, eight pm sharp, so if you are working late you need to be out before then or you'll be locked in until the morning. Please don't assume it's six, and don't assume it's ten either, eight in the evening is the cut-off. Second, and this applies to every single visitor without any exception, all visitors must carry a pass at all times while they are on the site. It isn't a paper ticket, and it isn't simply the identity card you brought from home; it is the site pass we issue you at reception, and security will ask to see that pass.", Q:[{"q":"Where on the site would you locate the front desk that greets arrivals?","a":"G"},{"q":"Which unit houses Building 1, containing the principal offices?","a":"A"},{"q":"Where is the storage depot for goods situated?","a":"B"},{"q":"In which spot will you find the staff dining hall?","a":"C"},{"q":"Whereabouts is the area set aside for parking vehicles?","a":"F"},{"q":"Where is the dock used for loading and unloading positioned?","a":"E"},{"q":"Which building contains the computer server facility?","a":"D"},{"q":"Where is the guards' post for site security placed?","a":"H"},{"q":"At what time in the evening do the main gates get locked?","a":"B","o":["Six in the evening","Eight in the evening","Ten in the evening"]},{"q":"What item is every guest obliged to keep on them throughout their visit?","a":"C","o":["Their identity card","An entry ticket","The site pass"]}]},
  {n:3, title:"Tutorial: dissertation structure", sp:["Tutor","Student"], intro:"a university tutor and a student discussing the plan for the student's dissertation", tr1:["Come in, sit down. I've had a good look through your dissertation plan over the weekend, and I'm pleased to say the topic itself is approved, there's no need to change the subject, it's well chosen and there's plenty for you to work with.","Oh, that's a real relief, thank you. I was a bit worried you might reject it, or say the whole thing was too unclear.","Not at all, it stands as it is. So let's talk about structure. How many chapters are you planning to write?","I'd originally sketched out four chapters... but honestly, the more I look at it, the more I think five would be clearer. Yes, let's go with five, splitting the analysis into two parts makes it read much better.","Five is sensible, I agree with that. And of those, which do you expect to be the longest chapter?","The literature review, by far. There's so much existing research to cover that it will easily be the biggest one, much longer than the introduction or the conclusion.","Good, that's exactly what I'd expect. And what about the total length, what is the word limit you're working to?","I thought it was ten thousand words at first, but I double-checked the course handbook, and the limit's actually twelve thousand. So twelve thousand is my ceiling, not eight thousand and not ten.","Twelve thousand, correct. Now, where are you going to put the methodology chapter?","Straight after the literature review, so it follows the review directly, rather than coming first or being right at the end."], tr2:["That's the right place for it. Now, there's one important thing missing from your plan as it stands, and it isn't the title and it isn't the references, because those are both there and perfectly fine.","Oh? What have I left out, then?","Your research questions. You need to state them clearly, right near the beginning, so the reader knows exactly what you are investigating. At the moment they're only implied.","Ah, you're quite right, I'll add the research questions explicitly, early on in the text.","Good. You should also add a section on limitations, not on the history of the field, and not on costs, but specifically the limitations of your own study, and put it near the end.","A limitations section near the end, understood. And can I ask when the deadline is?","The deadline is in March. Not January, and not June, but March, so you've got a decent stretch of time. One more thing: you submit online this year, through the portal, not on paper and not by post.","Online submission by March, got it. When shall we meet again to go through the next draft?","Let's say in two weeks. That's not as soon as next week, I want you to have time to make some real progress, but it's not as far off as a month either. Two weeks from today.","Two weeks from now, perfect. I'll have the research questions and the limitations section drafted by then. Thank you very much."], Q:[{"q":"What has the supervisor decided about the chosen subject?","a":"A","o":["It has been accepted","It has been turned down","It remains too vague"]},{"q":"How many chapters will the student now write?","a":"B","o":["Four","Five","Six"]},{"q":"Which chapter is expected to run the longest?","a":"B","o":["The opening section","The review of previous studies","The closing summary"]},{"q":"What is the maximum permitted number of words?","a":"C","o":["Eight thousand","Ten thousand","Twelve thousand"]},{"q":"Where in the structure will the methodology chapter sit?","a":"B","o":["Right at the start","Directly following the literature review","Right at the finish"]},{"q":"What element is absent from the plan at present?","a":"B","o":["A title","The research questions","The reference list"]},{"q":"What extra section does the tutor advise including?","a":"A","o":["The study's shortcomings","The background of the field","The financial outlay"]},{"q":"By when must the work be handed in?","a":"B","o":["January","March","June"]},{"q":"In what manner will the dissertation be handed in?","a":"B","o":["As a printed copy","Through the online portal","Sent by post"]},{"q":"How long until they will meet again?","a":"B","o":["In seven days","In a fortnight","In one month"]}]},
  {n:4, title:"Lecture: the psychology of habits", instr:"Complete the flow-chart tracing how habits form and change. Fill each gap with the precise word from the talk, staying within the word limit shown.", layout:"flow", flow:["Through constant repetition, a behaviour turns {1}, needing no conscious thought","|","Every habit runs as a loop of three stages: a cue, a routine and a {2}","|","Once the habit is set, the payoff is expected the moment the {3} shows up","|","This expectation of the payoff produces a {4}","|","To alter a habit, hold the cue and payoff steady but swap out the {5}","|","Difficult, because a lot of what we do is set off by our {6}","|","Habits shift most readily following a {7}, when familiar triggers vanish","|","Specialists highlight the strength of {8} habits","|","Modest daily adjustments {9} as time passes","|","Relying on willpower fails since habits operate {10}"], intro:"a lecturer talking to students about the psychology of habits, how they form and how they can be changed", tr1:"Today we examine how habits form and, just as importantly, how they can be changed. Let's begin with a definition. A habit is a behaviour that has become automatic through sheer repetition; you have done it so many times that you no longer have to think about it at all, which frees the conscious mind to attend to other things. Psychologists find it useful to describe every habit as a loop made up of three distinct parts. First comes a cue, the trigger that sets the behaviour off. Second comes the routine, the behaviour itself, the thing you actually do. And third comes a reward, the little payoff at the end that reinforces the whole cycle and makes the brain want to repeat it. Now here is the interesting part. Once a habit is firmly established, the timing shifts. The reward is no longer merely enjoyed at the very end; instead it is anticipated the moment the cue appears, because the brain, recognising the trigger, already expects the payoff to arrive. That anticipation, that expectation of a reward the instant the cue shows up, is precisely what creates a craving. So how do we use all this to change a habit? The most effective method is not to fight the whole loop, but to keep the same cue and the same reward, and simply replace the routine in between with a better one.", tr2:"But replacing the routine is easier said than done, and to understand why, we need to talk about willpower and about context. Many people assume that breaking a bad habit is simply a matter of trying harder, of gritting your teeth and forcing yourself. In fact, willpower alone is a surprisingly poor tool, and the reason is that habits run automatically, below the level of conscious choice; by the time you even notice the behaviour, it is already underway. Context matters here enormously. A great deal of our behaviour is not chosen deliberately at all, but triggered by our surroundings, as the places, objects and people around us act as cues without our ever realising it. This has a practical and rather hopeful consequence. Habits are easiest to change after a move, when you relocate to a new home or a new city, because the old cues are suddenly absent and those automatic triggers no longer fire. Finally, a word about scale. Experts stress the power of small habits. Rather than attempting one dramatic overhaul, they argue that tiny changes, each one almost trivial on its own but repeated faithfully every single day, compound over time, building on one another until they produce genuinely remarkable results. So to sum up the practical message of today's lecture: understand the loop of cue, routine and reward, do not rely on willpower alone, use a change of surroundings to your advantage, and above all trust the quiet power of small habits to accumulate.", Q:[{"q":"Repetition makes a behaviour become ______, so it no longer needs thought.","a":"automatic","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The three-part loop consists of a cue, a routine and a ______.","a":"reward","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"The payoff is expected the instant the ______ appears.","a":"cue","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Expecting the payoff gives rise to a ______.","a":"craving","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Changing a habit means keeping the cue and reward but exchanging the ______.","a":"routine","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"A great deal of our conduct is set off by our ______.","a":"surroundings","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Habits are simplest to alter just after a ______.","a":"move","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Experts underline the effectiveness of ______ habits.","a":"small","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Small everyday changes ______ as time goes on.","a":"compound","lim":"ONE WORD"},{"q":"Willpower is weak because habits function ______.","a":"automatically","lim":"ONE WORD"}]}
  ]}
];
